{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778698294781,"sessionID":"ses_1dd53290dffeoniMMBnoeZ6EmF","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_chFT1N9imKFi3j65UZmZMmHg","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\n+title: \"Qualify EX/MEM forwarding\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The forwarding unit currently gives EX/MEM priority for any instruction with reg_write set, including loads. A load's architectural writeback value is not available in EX/MEM; the existing load-use interlock ensures consumers only execute once the load has reached MEM/WB. Keeping loads in the EX/MEM forwarding match therefore leaves dead compare/select logic on the EX operand path and can momentarily select an unusable load address during held bubbles.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Qualify the EX/MEM bypass path so it is only eligible for results that are actually available in EX/MEM: ALU, LUI/AUIPC, and JAL/JALR link values. Pass a compact non-load indicator, or mem_to_reg/mem_read, from core.sv into forward_unit and add it to the EX/MEM priority condition for both rs1 and rs2.\n+\n+  This preserves all pipeline timing, RVFI metadata, load-use stalls, and MEM/WB load forwarding, but removes an impossible bypass case from the highest-priority forwarding path. The expected benefit is modest Fmax improvement from simpler EX operand select logic with essentially no IPC downside.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX/MEM bypass-eligible input and require it in the rs1/rs2 EX/MEM forwarding priority checks so loads are never selected from the unavailable EX/MEM address result.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the forwarding unit's new EX/MEM eligibility input from the existing EX/MEM control state, using non-load writeback instructions as bypassable and preserving the current MEM/WB forwarding path.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\n+title: \"Qualify EX/MEM forwarding\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The forwarding unit currently gives EX/MEM priority for any instruction with reg_write set, including loads. A load's architectural writeback value is not available in EX/MEM; the existing load-use interlock ensures consumers only execute once the load has reached MEM/WB. Keeping loads in the EX/MEM forwarding match therefore leaves dead compare/select logic on the EX operand path and can momentarily select an unusable load address during held bubbles.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Qualify the EX/MEM bypass path so it is only eligible for results that are actually available in EX/MEM: ALU, LUI/AUIPC, and JAL/JALR link values. Pass a compact non-load indicator, or mem_to_reg/mem_read, from core.sv into forward_unit and add it to the EX/MEM priority condition for both rs1 and rs2.\n+\n+  This preserves all pipeline timing, RVFI metadata, load-use stalls, and MEM/WB load forwarding, but removes an impossible bypass case from the highest-priority forwarding path. The expected benefit is modest Fmax improvement from simpler EX operand select logic with essentially no IPC downside.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX/MEM bypass-eligible input and require it in the rs1/rs2 EX/MEM forwarding priority checks so loads are never selected from the unavailable EX/MEM address result.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the forwarding unit's new EX/MEM eligibility input from the existing EX/MEM control state, using non-load writeback instructions as bypassable and preserving the current MEM/WB forwarding path.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\n+title: \"Qualify EX/MEM forwarding\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The forwarding unit currently gives EX/MEM priority for any instruction with reg_write set, including loads. A load's architectural writeback value is not available in EX/MEM; the existing load-use interlock ensures consumers only execute once the load has reached MEM/WB. Keeping loads in the EX/MEM forwarding match therefore leaves dead compare/select logic on the EX operand path and can momentarily select an unusable load address during held bubbles.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Qualify the EX/MEM bypass path so it is only eligible for results that are actually available in EX/MEM: ALU, LUI/AUIPC, and JAL/JALR link values. Pass a compact non-load indicator, or mem_to_reg/mem_read, from core.sv into forward_unit and add it to the EX/MEM priority condition for both rs1 and rs2.\n+\n+  This preserves all pipeline timing, RVFI metadata, load-use stalls, and MEM/WB load forwarding, but removes an impossible bypass case from the highest-priority forwarding path. The expected benefit is modest Fmax improvement from simpler EX operand select logic with essentially no IPC downside.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX/MEM bypass-eligible input and require it in the rs1/rs2 EX/MEM forwarding priority checks so loads are never selected from the unavailable EX/MEM address result.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the forwarding unit's new EX/MEM eligibility input from the existing EX/MEM control state, using non-load writeback instructions as bypassable and preserving the current MEM/WB forwarding path.\"\n","additions":17,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778698294779,"end":1778698294781}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0eec88a9aa6df6b1016a04c824c5c4819baa1c46ab0ee19072"}},"id":"prt_e22add0100015ojnIymzZZPgeN","sessionID":"ses_1dd53290dffeoniMMBnoeZ6EmF","messageID":"msg_e22adc8bc001qM515q2wWDne1G"}}
