{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778700127780,"sessionID":"ses_1dd36dad0ffeBTl8OsSWKmNkc9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Vx8tRUtOu4vBDEorNAD3S1o8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r12s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r12s0\n+title: \"Drop dead AUIPC ALU mux\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best bench core already precomputes PC+imm in ID and uses that registered value for AUIPC writeback in EX. However, the EX ALU input path still contains an is_auipc-controlled mux that forces alu_a to zero even though the ALU result is ignored for AUIPC. That mux adds control fanout and operand routing to the common ALU path used by arithmetic, load/store address generation, and branch support.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the AUIPC special case from the ALU operand-a selection in rtl/ex_stage.sv, leaving alu_a equal to the forwarded rs1 value for all instructions. AUIPC architectural behavior remains unchanged because ex_mem.alu_result already selects the registered pc_imm_target when ctrl.is_auipc is set, and RVFI pc/data metadata continues to flow through the existing pipeline registers.\n+\n+  This is a small Fmax-oriented cleanup that removes one unnecessary 32-bit mux from the hot EX operand path without adding state, changing stalls, touching RV32M arithmetic, altering prediction, or modifying the nret=1 RVFI contract. The expected gain is modest but the risk is lower than prior gating attempts because it deletes dead logic instead of adding new op-dependent gating.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the ctrl.is_auipc mux from alu_a selection because AUIPC writeback already uses the registered pc_imm_target instead of the ALU output.\"\n*** End Patch"