{"type":"text","timestamp":1778680245110,"sessionID":"ses_1de65a163ffegxtgkvTpV3MIF0","part":{"id":"prt_e219aa7f9001XdRLBccfhLhxIf","messageID":"msg_e219a9200001wMv7warntjFX7S","sessionID":"ses_1de65a163ffegxtgkvTpV3MIF0","type":"text","text":"Prior micro-opt attempts show the successful path was Fmax-oriented ALU simplification; IPC shortcuts around load-use and branch prediction either broke correctness or lost Fmax. I’ll propose another narrow Fmax micro-optimization that avoids changing pipeline timing: reduce high-fanout control bundle width by carrying predecoded “writes rd” and memory mask intent where it cuts decode/control fanout.","time":{"start":1778680244217,"end":1778680245109},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0ba864b62d62158c016a0481b41bd08198b229922ab7e6c7a4","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778680266029,"sessionID":"ses_1de65a163ffegxtgkvTpV3MIF0","part":{"id":"prt_e219af929001H1Pll478eHH0CW","messageID":"msg_e219a9200001wMv7warntjFX7S","sessionID":"ses_1de65a163ffegxtgkvTpV3MIF0","type":"text","text":"I’m writing the hypothesis as a narrow `alu.sv` micro-optimization: share/gate DIV/REM hardware analogously to the already-successful MUL sharing, preserving single-cycle RV32M semantics and ALTOPS behavior.","time":{"start":1778680265001,"end":1778680266028},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0ba864b62d62158c016a0481c8dc3c8198aab48ed45bfc37c5","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778680285291,"sessionID":"ses_1de65a163ffegxtgkvTpV3MIF0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_9xusHbnROr0GPzE1P1vG7viF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\n+title: \"Share RV32M divide datapath\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best result came from a narrow ALU micro-optimization: sharing and gating the MUL-family datapath improved Tang Nano Fmax without adding pipeline stalls. The remaining RV32M divide/remainder logic still exposes separate signed and unsigned / and % operators in the combinational ALU case, which can leave yosys with multiple wide divider/remainder cones and extra muxing even though CoreMark mostly executes simpler RV32I operations.\n+\n+  Prior attempts to move M-extension work into a multicycle side unit regressed because the added pipeline holds cost more than the Fmax gain. A same-cycle datapath sharing pass keeps the existing timing model and RVFI retirement behavior while attacking the remaining large arithmetic hardware in the common EX block.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/alu.sv so DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU use one shared operand-normalization path, one gated unsigned quotient/remainder datapath, and lightweight sign/zero correction for the four RV32M results. Force divider operands to harmless constants outside divide/remainder ops so non-M ALU operations do not carry live divider input routing through synthesis, mirroring the successful multiply gating strategy.\n+\n+  This should reduce LUT pressure and improve Fmax without changing pipeline depth, adding stalls, altering the nret=1 RVFI contract, or weakening illegal-instruction/trap semantics. RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS behavior remains unchanged, and real RV32M corner cases such as divide-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 are preserved in the non-ALTOPS branch.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Share and gate the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU datapath with exact RV32M corner-case behavior and unchanged RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions.\"\n+  - file: test/test_alu.py\n+    description: \"Retain or extend divider and remainder vectors for divide-by-zero, signed overflow, sign correction, and unsigned cases after the shared datapath refactor.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\n+title: \"Share RV32M divide datapath\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best result came from a narrow ALU micro-optimization: sharing and gating the MUL-family datapath improved Tang Nano Fmax without adding pipeline stalls. The remaining RV32M divide/remainder logic still exposes separate signed and unsigned / and % operators in the combinational ALU case, which can leave yosys with multiple wide divider/remainder cones and extra muxing even though CoreMark mostly executes simpler RV32I operations.\n+\n+  Prior attempts to move M-extension work into a multicycle side unit regressed because the added pipeline holds cost more than the Fmax gain. A same-cycle datapath sharing pass keeps the existing timing model and RVFI retirement behavior while attacking the remaining large arithmetic hardware in the common EX block.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/alu.sv so DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU use one shared operand-normalization path, one gated unsigned quotient/remainder datapath, and lightweight sign/zero correction for the four RV32M results. Force divider operands to harmless constants outside divide/remainder ops so non-M ALU operations do not carry live divider input routing through synthesis, mirroring the successful multiply gating strategy.\n+\n+  This should reduce LUT pressure and improve Fmax without changing pipeline depth, adding stalls, altering the nret=1 RVFI contract, or weakening illegal-instruction/trap semantics. RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS behavior remains unchanged, and real RV32M corner cases such as divide-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 are preserved in the non-ALTOPS branch.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Share and gate the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU datapath with exact RV32M corner-case behavior and unchanged RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions.\"\n+  - file: test/test_alu.py\n+    description: \"Retain or extend divider and remainder vectors for divide-by-zero, signed overflow, sign correction, and unsigned cases after the shared datapath refactor.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypothes