{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778684172132,"sessionID":"ses_1de299b7dffeTEp56YowcVuBua","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_zRSJAD1ZVJcAsDSDlrCIwd8M","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r1s0 (improvement, +40.85%): Sharing the MUL-family datapath into one op-selected 33x33 multiplier and zeroing non-M inputs can dramatically improve Tang Nano Fmax by removing always-live parallel product logic from common RV32I ALU paths.\n2: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (regression, +29.37%): Moving RV32M into a blocking multicycle side unit can regress CoreMark because m_stall-driven IF/ID/EX holds and EX/MEM bubbles cost more than removing the remaining M arithmetic from the common ALU path.\n3: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (regression, +4.05%): ID-stage branch prediction must carry the decoded target as the branch's predicted_pc_next metadata, otherwise EX compares against IF's pre-decode fall-through PC and still flushes nominally correct backward-branch predictions.\n4: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Load-use source qualification must be driven by the decoder's exact operand-use semantics; opcode-only hazard logic plus ID/EX rs zeroing can desynchronize forwarding/RVFI metadata and break cosim.\n5: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r2s1 (regression, -12.80%): Same-cycle MEM load-data to EX forwarding can lengthen the dmem_rdata/load-extension/forward-select/ALU path enough that lost Fmax outweighs any CoreMark load-use bubble savings.\n6: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r2s2 (regression, -41.84%): ID-stage backward-branch prediction can lose more FPGA fitness than it recovers because imem_data-to-decode-to-imm-add-to-PC redirect logic lengthens the fetch critical path; fetch-side prediction needs registered metadata or a BTB-like path.\n7: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -55.68%): Sharing DIV/REM through signed abs/restore muxes and simultaneous quotient/remainder cones can worsen Tang Nano timing; RV32M divider optimizations need to avoid adding normalization logic to the same-cycle ALU critical path.\n8: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -22.81%): A full registered IF/ID boundary can lose CoreMark fitness because the extra fetch-to-decode latency and branch/load-use hold/flush interactions outweigh any Fmax gained from removing imem_data from decode fanout.\n9: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (broken, n/a): Fetch BTBs add mutable predictor arrays and predicted-PC metadata to the formal PC path, which can make riscv-formal BMC time out even before performance is measurable.\n\n(End of file - total 9 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r1s0 (improvement, +40.85%): Sharing the MUL-family datapath into one op-selected 33x33 multiplier and zeroing non-M inputs can dramatically improve Tang Nano Fmax by removing always-live parallel product logic from common RV32I ALU paths.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (regression, +29.37%): Moving RV32M into a blocking multicycle side unit can regress CoreMark because m_stall-driven IF/ID/EX holds and EX/MEM bubbles cost more than removing the remaining M arithmetic from the common ALU path.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (regression, +4.05%): ID-stage branch prediction must carry the decoded target as the branch's predicted_pc_next metadata, otherwise EX compares against IF's pre-decode fall-through PC and still flushes nominally correct backward-branch predictions.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Load-use source qualification must be driven by the decoder's exact operand-use semantics; opcode-only hazard logic plus ID/EX rs zeroing can desynchronize forwarding/RVFI metadata and break cosim.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r2s1 (regression, -12.80%): Same-cycle MEM load-data to EX forwarding can lengthen the dmem_rdata/load-extension/forward-select/ALU path enough that lost Fmax outweighs any CoreMark load-use bubble savings.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r2s2 (regression, -41.84%): ID-stage backward-branch prediction can lose more FPGA fitness than it recovers because imem_data-to-decode-to-imm-add-to-PC redirect logic lengthens the fetch critical path; fetch-side prediction needs registered metadata or a BTB-like path.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -55.68%): Sharing DIV/REM through signed abs/restore muxes and simultaneous quotient/remainder cones can worsen Tang Nano timing; RV32M divider optimizations need to avoid adding normalization logic to the same-cycle ALU critical path.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -22.81%): A full registered IF/ID boundary can lose CoreMark fitness because the extra fetch-to-decode latency and branch/load-use hold/flush interactions outweigh any Fmax gained from removing imem_data from decode fanout.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (broken, n/a): Fetch BTBs add mutable predictor arrays and predicted-PC metadata to the formal PC path, which can make riscv-formal BMC time out even before performance is measurable.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778684172118,"end":1778684172131}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e0efd87cc17e39e016a04910bb6d4819ab2579341601b4aaf"}},"id":"prt_e21d696820018amH2ZhyGOc3ay","sessionID":"ses_1de299b7dffeTEp56YowcVuBua","messageID":"msg_e21d665a900143JBdutm3L8ee2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778684172294,"sessionID":"ses_1de299b7dffeTEp56YowcVuBua","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_pQaHXp4lsjGDVYctt6IozsNy","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"category: micro_opt|micro_opt|hyp-20260513-001-r1s0|hyp-20260513-002-r2s1|hyp-20260513-001-r3s0","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 5 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-5172724\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-13T13:13:53.650168Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Gate and share M-extension ALU hardware\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally forms three independent 64-bit products for every instruction, even though CoreMark is dominated by RV32I arithmetic, branches, and memory traffic. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely burns LUTs and routing and may sit on or near the EX-stage critical path despite M operations being rare in the benchmark.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally forms three independent 64-bit products for every instruction, even though CoreMark is dominated by RV32I arithmetic, branches, and memory traffic. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely burns LUTs and routing and may sit on or near the EX-stage critical path despite M operations being rare in the benchmark.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv so MUL-family operations use a single op-selected signedness/extension path and only feed meaningful operands into the multiplier when the decoded ALU op is an M multiply. Keep the existing RV32M results and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS behavior unchanged, but make non-M ALU operations see simpler combinational logic and give yosys/nextpnr less multiplier-related muxing and routing to optimize through. This is a micro-optimization aimed primarily at improving Fmax and secondarily reducing LUT pressure without changing pipeline timing, RVFI behavior, or architectural state.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Share multiply operand preparation across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU and gate multiplier inputs for non-multiply ALU ops while preserving exact RV32M and ALTOPS semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Extend or retain M-extension ALU vectors to guard signed, unsigned, and mixed-sign multiply corner cases after the multiplier datapath refactor.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"c...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Suppress false load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current hazard unit stalls on any instruction following a load when its\\nrd matches bits [19:15] or [24:20] of the next instruction. Those bit fields\\nare not always live source operands: I-type ALU/load/JALR only reads rs1,\\nstores and branches read both, and U/J/FENCE/EBREAK read neither. False\\nload-use bubbles directly reduce CoreMark iterations/cycle and become more\\nexpensive under the random instruction/data stall model.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current hazard unit stalls on any instruction following a load when its\\nrd matches bits [19:15] or [24:20] of the next instruction. Those bit fields\\nare not always live source operands: I-type ALU/load/JALR only reads rs1,\\nstores and branches read both, and U/J/FENCE/EBREAK read neither. False\\nload-use bubbles directly reduce CoreMark iterations/cycle and become more\\nexpensive under the random instruction/data stall model.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add lightweight source-use qualification to the load-use hazard path so the\\npipeline only inserts the one-cycle bubble when the IF/ID instruction will\\nactually consume the matching source register. Derive rs1_used and rs2_used\\ncombinationally from opcode/funct class in the hazard unit or adjacent decode\\nwiring, preserving the existing forwarding, RVFI ordering, and memory-stall\\nbehavior. This is a small IPC-focused micro-optimization with low Fmax risk\\nbecause it removes unnecessary stalls without changing pipeline depth or the\\ncritical ALU/M-extension datapath.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Qualify load-use detection with source-register usage so rd matches against immediate, U/J, FENCE, or EBREAK bitfields do not stall the pipeline.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass the IF/ID instruction opcode context needed for rs1_used/r...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Bypass ready load data to EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline pays a mandatory one-cycle load-use bubble whenever the instruction immediately after a load consumes the loaded register. CoreMark's list and matrix kernels contain many pointer and array dependent loads, and the benchmark bus model often has dmem ready in the same cycle. Recovering those bubbles should improve iterations/cycle without changing the retirement width or adding the broad pipeline stalls that hurt the prior structural M-unit attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline pays a mandatory one-cycle load-use bubble whenever the instruction immediately after a load consumes the loaded register. CoreMark's list and matrix kernels contain many pointer and array dependent loads, and the benchmark bus model often has dmem ready in the same cycle. Recovering those bubbles should improve iterations/cycle without changing the retirement width or adding the broad pipeline stalls that hurt the prior structural M-unit attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a MEM-to-EX load-result bypass path for the specific case where the instruction in EX/MEM is a load, dmem is ready, and the younger ID/EX instruction uses that load's rd. The MEM stage already computes sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally before the MEM/WB register; expose that value and let the forwarding network select it for EX operands when dmem_ready is high. Keep the existing load-use interlock only for dmem stalls or cases where the load data is not yet ready, so correctness and RVFI ordering remain unchanged while ready loads avoid the one-cycle bubble.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"If needed, add a compact forwarding selector encoding for the new MEM-stage load-data bypass while preserving existing pipeline bundle semantics.\"}, {\"file\"...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Share RV32M divide datapath\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from a narrow ALU micro-optimization: sharing and gating the MUL-family datapath improved Tang Nano Fmax without adding pipeline stalls. The remaining RV32M divide/remainder logic still exposes separate signed and unsigned / and % operators in the combinational ALU case, which can leave yosys with multiple wide divider/remainder cones and extra muxing even though CoreMark mostly executes simpler RV32I operations.\\n\\nPrior attempts to move M-extension work into a multicycle side unit regressed because the added pipeline holds cost more than the Fmax gain. A same-cycle datapath sharing pass keeps the existing timing model and RVFI retirement behavior while attacking the remaining large arithmetic hardware in the common EX block.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from a narrow ALU micro-optimization: sharing and gating the MUL-family datapath improved Tang Nano Fmax without adding pipeline stalls. The remaining RV32M divide/remainder logic still exposes separate signed and unsigned / and % operators in the combinational ALU case, which can leave yosys with multiple wide divider/remainder cones and extra muxing even though CoreMark mostly executes simpler RV32I operations.\\n\\nPrior attempts to move M-extension work into a multicycle side unit regressed because the added pipeline holds cost more than the Fmax gain. A same-cycle datapath sharing pass keeps the existing timing model and RVFI retirement behavior while attacking the remaining large arithmetic hardware in the common EX block.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv so DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU use one shared operand-normalization path, one gated unsigned quotient/remainder datapath, and lightweight sign/zero correction for the four RV32M results. Force divider operands to harmless constants outside divide/remainder ops so non-M ALU operations do not c...","metadata":{"matches":5,"truncated":false},"title":"category: micro_opt|micro_opt|hyp-20260513-001-r1s0|hyp-20260513-002-r2s1|hyp-20260513-001-r3s0","time":{"start":1778684172257,"end":1778684172292}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e0efd87cc17e39e016a04910bb6e4819a8f42788ae765cefc"}},"id":"prt_e21d6978d001GX4sLngABCLjKO","sessionID":"ses_1de299b7dffeTEp56YowcVuBua","messageID":"msg_e21d665a900143JBdutm3L8ee2"}}
