{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778684225550,"sessionID":"ses_1de299b7dffeTEp56YowcVuBua","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_UJItW8ej66rLEcNmixayvVBz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Remove regfile reset fanout\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current register file synchronously resets all 32 architectural registers, which forces reset muxing and routing across 1024 state bits. On a small FPGA this can prevent efficient distributed-RAM inference and add reset fanout to a block that is read on the decode critical path.\n+\n+  RV32I only requires x0 to read as zero; the other architectural registers do not need a defined hardware reset value as long as software initializes the registers it uses and RVFI reports the actual values read. Removing this reset is a narrow micro-optimization aimed at improving Fmax and possibly LUT pressure without changing pipeline depth, stalls, forwarding, memory behavior, or retirement width.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/reg_file.sv so reset no longer clears regs[1:31]. Keep x0 hardwired through the existing read and write gating, preserve write-first same-cycle bypass behavior, and leave the write port synchronous.\n+\n+  This should let yosys/nextpnr implement the 32x32 two-read/one-write file with less reset-related muxing and routing, potentially improving the decode/regfile-read timing path and reducing LUT/FF pressure. Because the change only affects power-on contents of nonzero registers, CoreMark and formal should remain correct if all live software state is initialized architecturally through writes before use.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the synchronous reset loop over regs[0:31] while preserving x0 read-as-zero, x0 write suppression, and write-first bypass semantics.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Remove regfile reset fanout\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current register file synchronously resets all 32 architectural registers, which forces reset muxing and routing across 1024 state bits. On a small FPGA this can prevent efficient distributed-RAM inference and add reset fanout to a block that is read on the decode critical path.\n+\n+  RV32I only requires x0 to read as zero; the other architectural registers do not need a defined hardware reset value as long as software initializes the registers it uses and RVFI reports the actual values read. Removing this reset is a narrow micro-optimization aimed at improving Fmax and possibly LUT pressure without changing pipeline depth, stalls, forwarding, memory behavior, or retirement width.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/reg_file.sv so reset no longer clears regs[1:31]. Keep x0 hardwired through the existing read and write gating, preserve write-first same-cycle bypass behavior, and leave the write port synchronous.\n+\n+  This should let yosys/nextpnr implement the 32x32 two-read/one-write file with less reset-related muxing and routing, potentially improving the decode/regfile-read timing path and reducing LUT/FF pressure. Because the change only affects power-on contents of nonzero registers, CoreMark and formal should remain correct if all live software state is initialized architecturally through writes before use.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the synchronous reset loop over regs[0:31] while preserving x0 read-as-zero, x0 write suppression, and write-first bypass semantics.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\n+title: \"Remove regfile reset fanout\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current register file synchronously resets all 32 architectural registers, which forces reset muxing and routing across 1024 state bits. On a small FPGA this can prevent efficient distributed-RAM inference and add reset fanout to a block that is read on the decode critical path.\n+\n+  RV32I only requires x0 to read as zero; the other architectural registers do not need a defined hardware reset value as long as software initializes the registers it uses and RVFI reports the actual values read. Removing this reset is a narrow micro-optimization aimed at improving Fmax and possibly LUT pressure without changing pipeline depth, stalls, forwarding, memory behavior, or retirement width.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/reg_file.sv so reset no longer clears regs[1:31]. Keep x0 hardwired through the existing read and write gating, preserve write-first same-cycle bypass behavior, and leave the write port synchronous.\n+\n+  This should let yosys/nextpnr implement the 32x32 two-read/one-write file with less reset-related muxing and routing, potentially improving the decode/regfile-read timing path and reducing LUT/FF pressure. Because the change only affects power-on contents of nonzero registers, CoreMark and formal should remain correct if all live software state is initialized architecturally through writes before use.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the synchronous reset loop over regs[0:31] while preserving x0 read-as-zero, x0 write suppression, and write-first bypass semantics.\"\n","additions":17,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r4s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778684225545,"end":1778684225549}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0d43855bae9d3e60016a0491310a0881988c511b8d51507ef9"}},"id":"prt_e21d7283d001QtLy1JVAp3UqxH","sessionID":"ses_1de299b7dffeTEp56YowcVuBua","messageID":"msg_e21d717cf001mSmAWgJwUROob6"}}
