e is initialized architecturally through writes before use.\n12: expected_impact:\n13:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n14:   confidence: medium\n15: changes:\n16:   - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n17:     description: \"Remove the synchronous reset loop over regs[0:31] while preserving x0 read-as-zero, x0 write suppression, and write-first bypass semantics.\"\n\n(End of file - total 17 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\ntitle: \"Remove regfile reset fanout\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current register file synchronously resets all 32 architectural registers, which forces reset muxing and routing across 1024 state bits. On a small FPGA this can prevent efficient distributed-RAM inference and add reset fanout to a block that is read on the decode critical path.\n\n  RV32I only requires x0 to read as zero; the other architectural registers do not need a defined hardware reset value as long as software initializes the registers it uses and RVFI reports the actual values read. Removing this reset is a narrow micro-optimization aimed at improving Fmax and possibly LUT pressure without changing pipeline depth, stalls, forwarding, memory behavior, or retirement width.\nhypothesis: |\n  Refactor rtl/reg_file.sv so reset no longer clears regs[1:31]. Keep x0 hardwired through the existing read and write gating, preserve write-first same-cycle bypass behavior, and leave the write port synchronous.\n\n  This should let yosys/nextpnr implement the 32x32 two-read/one-write file with less reset-related muxing and routing, potentially improving the decode/regfile-read timing path and reducing LUT/FF pressure. Because the change only affects power-on contents of nonzero registers, CoreMark and formal should remain correct if all live software state is initialized architecturally through writes before use.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n    description: \"Remove the synchronous r