{"type":"text","timestamp":1778697329264,"sessionID":"ses_1dd6139bdffeUXjFvXkp55vXe1","part":{"id":"prt_e229f58f7001MrSFNiseL0udo0","messageID":"msg_e229ef886001I0JHOnckGBEMPT","sessionID":"ses_1dd6139bdffeUXjFvXkp55vXe1","type":"text","text":"The prior micro-opt history strongly favors behavior-preserving datapath cleanup and disfavors added predictors, queues, source-use metadata, divider rewrites, and packed-struct churn. I’m going to write a narrow hypothesis around reset/load-enable pressure on pipeline registers while preserving valid-gated architectural behavior.","time":{"start":1778697328887,"end":1778697329263},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0bcb2a42d0365415016a04c470c5ac819bb52dab380863a0d2","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778697379594,"sessionID":"ses_1dd6139bdffeUXjFvXkp55vXe1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_eBYmdVs6UaqQUgMqKDSiP5Pz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\n+title: Trim pipeline reset muxes\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best successful changes for this core have been narrow timing and routing cleanups that preserve the five-stage behavior, while recent predictor, buffer, divider, and metadata edits mostly regressed. The current pipeline still resets entire packed ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB records, adding reset muxing and fanout to many datapath bits whose values are architecturally ignored whenever valid is low.\n+\n+  Unlike removing reset from the architectural register file, trimming reset on invalid pipeline payload fields should not expose software-visible state. It targets placement and Fmax pressure in stage registers without changing IPC, branch policy, memory timing, RVFI order, or the nret=1 interface.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor the pipeline stage registers so reset clears the valid bits and the small set of side-effecting control bits that can drive writes, memory requests, traps, or hazard decisions, while non-side-effect payload fields are either left unchanged or only written on normal captures. Keep MEM/WB and top-level RVFI outputs deterministic by ensuring invalid retirements report valid=0 and no register or memory side effects, and qualify any hazard/memory-op checks with stage valid where needed.\n+\n+  This should remove a broad layer of reset muxes and reset routing from PC, instruction, operand, immediate, ALU-result, and RVFI metadata flops. The expected benefit is modest but potentially positive Fmax on Tang Nano 20K, with lower risk than adding new state machines or datapath muxes because the architectural behavior of valid instructions remains unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Reset only the ID/EX valid and side-effecting control state needed to make a bubble harmless; avoid reset muxes on ignored payload fields.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Apply the same valid/control-only reset discipline to EX/MEM while preserving redirect, trap, reg_write, and memory side-effect semantics for real instructions.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Keep MEM/WB invalid cycles side-effect-free and RVFI-safe while reducing unnecessary reset/load muxing on payload fields where possible.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"If needed, qualify memory-stall and hazard side-effect checks with pipeline valid so unreset invalid payload bits cannot create false stalls or requests.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\n+title: Trim pipeline reset muxes\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best successful changes for this core have been narrow timing and routing cleanups that preserve the five-stage behavior, while recent predictor, buffer, divider, and metadata edits mostly regressed. The current pipeline still resets entire packed ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB records, adding reset muxing and fanout to many datapath bits whose values are architecturally ignored whenever valid is low.\n+\n+  Unlike removing reset from the architectural register file, trimming reset on invalid pipeline payload fields should not expose software-visible state. It targets placement and Fmax pressure in stage registers without changing IPC, branch policy, memory timing, RVFI order, or the nret=1 interface.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor the pipeline stage registers so reset clears the valid bits and the small set of side-effecting control bits that can drive writes, memory requests, traps, or hazard decisions, while non-side-effect payload fields are either left unchanged or only written on normal captures. Keep MEM/WB and top-level RVFI outputs deterministic by ensuring invalid retirements report valid=0 and no register or memory side effects, and qualify any hazard/memory-op checks with stage valid where needed.\n+\n+  This should remove a broad layer of reset muxes and reset routing from PC, instruction, operand, immediate, ALU-result, and RVFI metadata flops. The expected benefit is modest but potentially positive Fmax on Tang Nano 20K, with lower risk than adding new state machines or datapath muxes because the architectural behavior of valid instructions remains unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Reset only the ID/EX valid and side-effecting control state needed to make a bubble harmless; avoid reset muxes on ignored payload fields.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Apply the same valid/control-only reset discipline to EX/MEM while preserving redirect, trap, reg_write, and memory side-effect semantics for real instructions.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Keep MEM/WB invalid cycles side-effect-free and RVFI-safe while reducing unnecessary reset/load muxing on payload fields where possible.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"If needed, qualify memory-stall and hazard side-effect checks with pipeline valid so unreset invalid payload bits cannot create false stalls or requests.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\n+title: Trim pipeline reset muxes\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best successful changes for this core have been narrow timing and routing cleanups that preserve the five-stage behavior, while recent predictor, buffer, divider, and metadata edits mostly regressed. The current pipeline still resets entire packed ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB records, adding reset muxing and fanout to many datapath bits whose values are architecturally ignored whenever valid is low.\n+\n+  Unlike removing reset from the architectural register file, trimming reset on invalid pipeline payload fields should not expose software-visible state. It targets placement and Fmax pressure in stage registers without changing IPC, branch policy, memory timing, RVFI order, or the nret=1 interface.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor the pipeline stage registers so reset clears the valid bits and the small set of side-effecting control bits that can drive writes, memory requests, traps, or hazard decisions, while non-side-effect payload fields are either left unchanged or only written on normal captures. Keep MEM/WB and top-level RVFI outputs deterministic by ensuring invalid retirements report valid=0 and no register or memory side effects, and qualify any hazard/memory-op checks with stage valid where needed.\n+\n+  This should remove a broad layer of reset muxes and reset routing from PC, instruction, operand, immediate, ALU-result, and RVFI metadata flops. The expected benefit is modest but potentially positive Fmax on Tang Nano 20K, with lower risk than adding new state machines or datapath muxes because the architectural behavior of valid instructions remains unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Reset only the ID/EX valid and side-effecting control state needed to make a bubble harmless; avoid reset muxes on ignored payload fields.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Apply the same valid/control-only reset discipline to EX/MEM while preserving redirect, trap, reg_write, and memory side-effect semantics for real instructions.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Keep MEM/WB invalid cycles side-effect-free and RVFI-safe while reducing unnecessary reset/load muxing on payload fields where possible.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"If needed, qualify memory-stall and hazard side-effect checks with pipeline valid so unreset invalid payload bits cannot create false stalls or requests.\"\n","additions":23,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778697379581,"end":1778697379592}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0bcb2a42d0365415016a04c48e9ef4819b9a8f7412774068e1"}},"id":"prt_e229fcd9a0014quqo1EN7CJtA5","sessionID":"ses_1dd6139bdffeUXjFvXkp55vXe1","messageID":"msg_e229ef886001I0JHOnckGBEMPT"}}
