{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778698234869,"sessionID":"ses_1dd5328a7ffeTbjzPWUt3IohU4","part":{"id":"prt_e22ad2bf4001k6joIaqrJsyHGM","messageID":"msg_e22ad28390025JpBOQACj5qXz3","sessionID":"ses_1dd5328a7ffeTbjzPWUt3IohU4","snapshot":"f186b910fa79b99df0e8c02a85575cc003af85e6","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778698261431,"sessionID":"ses_1dd5328a7ffeTbjzPWUt3IohU4","part":{"id":"prt_e22ad8920001JpOXRWUp2SCxmF","messageID":"msg_e22ad28390025JpBOQACj5qXz3","sessionID":"ses_1dd5328a7ffeTbjzPWUt3IohU4","type":"text","text":"I’m writing a single structural hypothesis: move only DIV/REM out of the single-cycle ALU into a multicycle divider, while keeping the successful single-cycle shared MUL datapath intact. This targets the remaining expensive combinational arithmetic without repeating the earlier full RV32M side-unit mistake that stalled common CoreMark multiplies.","time":{"start":1778698258720,"end":1778698261430},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_001449a7732829c9016a04c8129af88198bf26ef93e7309b25","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778698290026,"sessionID":"ses_1dd5328a7ffeTbjzPWUt3IohU4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_ekSrvDEzT12xhj7i1uHVEkw3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\n+title: \"Multicycle divider only\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already gained most of its Fmax by sharing the MUL-family datapath, but DIV/REM still live as full combinational operators inside the normal ALU result mux. Prior attempts show that moving all RV32M work into a side unit regresses because CoreMark uses multiply enough that broad M stalls are costly, and operand gating alone does not remove the divider cones from synthesis.\n+\n+  A narrower structural split should target only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. These operations are rare in the timed CoreMark hot path compared with adds, loads, stores, branches, and multiplies, so paying multicycle latency for divider-class instructions is likely cheaper than carrying same-cycle divide/remainder hardware on every EX-stage timing path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the ALU's real DIV/REM combinational operators with a dedicated iterative divider/remainder unit that is invoked only when an ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, or ALU_REMU instruction reaches EX. Keep RV32I operations and the successful shared MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU datapath single-cycle in the existing ALU.\n+\n+  On a divider instruction, hold IF, ID, and the EX-stage instruction while the divider runs, then capture the completed quotient or remainder into EX/MEM and retire through the unchanged MEM/WB and RVFI path. Preserve the existing RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch as combinational stand-ins for formal, and implement exact RV32M divide-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 semantics in the real divider path.\n+\n+  This should reduce LUT/routing pressure and Fmax-critical EX result mux complexity more effectively than operand gating, while avoiding the earlier full-M-unit regression by not stalling ordinary MUL-heavy CoreMark code.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Remove real DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU operators from the normal combinational ALU path while keeping RV32I, MUL-family, and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS behavior intact.\"\n+  - file: rtl/div_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a small iterative RV32M divider/remainder unit with start/busy/done/result signals and exact divide-by-zero and signed-overflow semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Dispatch divider-class instructions to the new unit, hold the EX instruction until completion, and capture the completed result into EX/MEM without changing branch, memory, MUL, or RVFI metadata behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a divider-busy stall input so frontend and decode stages hold during a multicycle DIV/REM operation while existing dmem, imem, redirect, and load-use priorities remain intact.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the divider stall signal between EX and hazard control, preserving the nret=1 top-level IO and existing RVFI channel-0 retirement contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\n+title: \"Multicycle divider only\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already gained most of its Fmax by sharing the MUL-family datapath, but DIV/REM still live as full combinational operators inside the normal ALU result mux. Prior attempts show that moving all RV32M work into a side unit regresses because CoreMark uses multiply enough that broad M stalls are costly, and operand gating alone does not remove the divider cones from synthesis.\n+\n+  A narrower structural split should target only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. These operations are rare in the timed CoreMark hot path compared with adds, loads, stores, branches, and multiplies, so paying multicycle latency for divider-class instructions is likely cheaper than carrying same-cycle divide/remainder hardware on every EX-stage timing path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the ALU's real DIV/REM combinational operators with a dedicated iterative divider/remainder unit that is invoked only when an ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, or ALU_REMU instruction reaches EX. Keep RV32I operations and the successful shared MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU datapath single-cycle in the existing ALU.\n+\n+  On a divider instruction, hold IF, ID, and the EX-stage instruction while the divider runs, then capture the completed quotient or remainder into EX/MEM and retire through the unchanged MEM/WB and RVFI path. Preserve the existing RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch as combinational stand-ins for formal, and implement exact RV32M divide-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 semantics in the real divider path.\n+\n+  This should reduce LUT/routing pressure and Fmax-critical EX result mux complexity more effectively than operand gating, while avoiding the earlier full-M-unit regression by not stalling ordinary MUL-heavy CoreMark code.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Remove real DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU operators from the normal combinational ALU path while keeping RV32I, MUL-family, and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS behavior intact.\"\n+  - file: rtl/div_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a small iterative RV32M divider/remainder unit with start/busy/done/result signals and exact divide-by-zero and signed-overflow semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Dispatch divider-class instructions to the new unit, hold the EX instruction until completion, and capture the completed result into EX/MEM without changing branch, memory, MUL, or RVFI metadata behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a divider-busy stall input so frontend and decode stages hold during a multicycle DIV/REM operation while existing dmem, imem, redirect, and load-use priorities remain intact.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the divider stall signal between EX and hazard control, preserving the nret=1 top-level IO and existing RVFI channel-0 retirement contract.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\n+title: \"Multicycle divider only\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already gained most of its Fmax by sharing the MUL-family datapath, but DIV/REM still live as full combinational operators inside the normal ALU result mux. Prior attempts show that moving all RV32M work into a side unit regresses because CoreMark uses multiply enough that broad M stalls are costly, and operand gating alone does not remove the divider cones from synthesis.\n+\n+  A narrower structural split should target only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. These operations are rare in the timed CoreMark hot path compared with adds, loads, stores, branches, and multiplies, so paying multicycle latency for divider-class instructions is likely cheaper than carrying same-cycle divide/remainder hardware on every EX-stage timing path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the ALU's real DIV/REM combinational operators with a dedicated iterative divider/remainder unit that is invoked only when an ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, or ALU_REMU instruction reaches EX. Keep RV32I operations and the successful shared MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU datapath single-cycle in the existing ALU.\n+\n+  On a divider instruction, hold IF, ID, and the EX-stage instruction while the divider runs, then capture the completed quotient or remainder into EX/MEM and retire through the unchanged MEM/WB and RVFI path. Preserve the existing RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch as combinational stand-ins for formal, and implement exact RV32M divide-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 semantics in the real divider path.\n+\n+  This should reduce LUT/routing pressure and Fmax-critical EX result mux complexity more effectively than operand gating, while avoiding the earlier full-M-unit regression by not stalling ordinary MUL-heavy CoreMark code.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Remove real DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU operators from the normal combinational ALU path while keeping RV32I, MUL-family, and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS behavior intact.\"\n+  - file: rtl/div_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a small iterative RV32M divider/remainder unit with start/busy/done/result signals and exact divide-by-zero and signed-overflow semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Dispatch divider-class instructions to the new unit, hold the EX instruction until completion, and capture the completed result into EX/MEM without changing branch, memory, MUL, or RVFI metadata behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a divider-busy stall input so frontend and decode stages hold during a multicycle DIV/REM operation while existing dmem, imem, redirect, and load-use priorities remain intact.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the divider stall signal between EX and hazard control, preserving the nret=1 top-level IO and existing RVFI channel-0 retirement contract.\"\n","additions":27,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778698290023,"end":1778698290025}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_001449a7732829c9016a04c81555a48198b8976e21bfa143bd"}},"id":"prt_e22ad93b7001R8qPB9G4o0XOuO","sessionID":"ses_1dd5328a7ffeTbjzPWUt3IohU4","messageID":"msg_e22ad28390025JpBOQACj5qXz3"}}
