{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778700902089,"sessionID":"ses_1dd2a561effeaTIjFEKGAY0mBG","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_YWEXVZf0YaLWYFkjFbBP1lPh","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"category.*structural|structural|IF/ID|pipeline|stage|bypass|forward|hazard|MEM/WB|EX/MEM","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 36 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Gate and share M-extension ALU hardware\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally forms three independent 64-bit products for every instruction, even though CoreMark is dominated by RV32I arithmetic, branches, and memory traffic. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely burns LUTs and routing and may sit on or near the EX-stage critical path despite M operations being rare in the benchmark.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU unconditionally forms three independent 64-bit products for every instruction, even though CoreMark is dominated by RV32I arithmetic, branches, and memory traffic. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely burns LUTs and routing and may sit on or near the EX-stage critical path despite M operations being rare in the benchmark.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv so MUL-family operations use a single op-selected signedness/extension path and only feed meaningful operands into the multiplier when the decoded ALU op is an M multiply. Keep the existing RV32M results and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS behavior unchanged, but make non-M ALU operations see simpler combinational logic and give yosys/nextpnr less multiplier-related muxing and routing to optimize through. This is a micro-optimization aimed primarily at improving Fmax and secondarily reducing LUT pressure without changing pipeline timing, RVFI behavior, or architectural state.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Share multiply operand preparation across MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU and gate multiplier inputs for non-multiply ALU ops while preserving exact RV32M and ALTOPS semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Extend or retain M-extension ALU vectors to guard signed, unsigned, and mixed-sign multiply corner cases after the multiplier datapath refactor.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"c...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Move RV32M to multicycle side unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains full combinational RV32M multiply and divide logic inside the same ALU case as single-cycle integer operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely contributes a long critical path and high LUT pressure even though CoreMark's hot loop is dominated by simple integer, branch, and memory operations. Removing the divider and wide multiplier from the regular EX datapath should improve Fmax and may also improve placement by reducing EX fan-in.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains full combinational RV32M multiply and divide logic inside the same ALU case as single-cycle integer operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely contributes a long critical path and high LUT pressure even though CoreMark's hot loop is dominated by simple integer, branch, and memory operations. Removing the divider and wide multiplier from the regular EX datapath should improve Fmax and may also improve placement by reducing EX fan-in.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure the pipeline so RV32M operations dispatch from EX into a dedicated multicycle M unit while ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, jump, and address-generation operations remain single-cycle. When an M instruction reaches EX, hold IF/ID/EX behind it until the unit returns the result, then capture that result into EX/MEM and retire normally through the existing MEM/WB and RVFI path. This should preserve single-retire ordering and correctness while replacing the worst combinational arithmetic path with shorter iterative or staged logic; the added stalls should be infrequent enough in CoreMark to be outweighed by Fmax gains.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real multiply/divide/remainder operators from the normal combinational ALU path, keeping only simple RV32I operations and the ex...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Add tiny backward-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves every conditional branch in EX and then\\nflushes two younger wrong-path instructions on taken branches. CoreMark has\\nmany small loop backedges, so the static not-taken policy wastes cycles on the\\nhottest control-flow pattern while also exposing random instruction stalls to\\nextra refetch work.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves every conditional branch in EX and then\\nflushes two younger wrong-path instructions on taken branches. CoreMark has\\nmany small loop backedges, so the static not-taken policy wastes cycles on the\\nhottest control-flow pattern while also exposing random instruction stalls to\\nextra refetch work.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a minimal static predictor in fetch/decode that predicts backward\\nconditional branches taken and redirects the PC to the decoded B-immediate\\ntarget before EX. Carry predicted-next-PC metadata through ID/EX so EX can\\ndistinguish correct predictions from mispredictions, only flushing on actual\\nmismatches. This should remove most taken-loop branch penalties with very low\\nLUT cost and little Fmax risk compared with a dynamic BHT/BTB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles with predicted PC and predicted-taken metadata for branch recovery.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept an early decode redirect for backward branches and report the predicted next PC alongside the fetched instruction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect backward conditional branches from the fetched instruction, compute the B-immediate target, and pass prediction metadata into EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compare the predicted next PC against the resolved branch or jump next PC and redirec...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Suppress false load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current hazard unit stalls on any instruction following a load when its\\nrd matches bits [19:15] or [24:20] of the next instruction. Those bit fields\\nare not always live source operands: I-type ALU/load/JALR only reads rs1,\\nstores and branches read both, and U/J/FENCE/EBREAK read neither. False\\nload-use bubbles directly reduce CoreMark iterations/cycle and become more\\nexpensive under the random instruction/data stall model.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current hazard unit stalls on any instruction following a load when its\\nrd matches bits [19:15] or [24:20] of the next instruction. Those bit fields\\nare not always live source operands: I-type ALU/load/JALR only reads rs1,\\nstores and branches read both, and U/J/FENCE/EBREAK read neither. False\\nload-use bubbles directly reduce CoreMark iterations/cycle and become more\\nexpensive under the random instruction/data stall model.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add lightweight source-use qualification to the load-use hazard path so the\\npipeline only inserts the one-cycle bubble when the IF/ID instruction will\\nactually consume the matching source register. Derive rs1_used and rs2_used\\ncombinationally from opcode/funct class in the hazard unit or adjacent decode\\nwiring, preserving the existing forwarding, RVFI ordering, and memory-stall\\nbehavior. This is a small IPC-focused micro-optimization with low Fmax risk\\nbecause it removes unnecessary stalls without changing pipeline depth or the\\ncritical ALU/M-extension datapath.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Qualify load-use detection with source-register usage so rd matches against immediate, U/J, FENCE, or EBREAK bitfields do not stall the pipeline.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass the IF/ID instruction opcode context needed for rs1_used/r...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Bypass ready load data to EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline pays a mandatory one-cycle load-use bubble whenever the instruction immediately after a load consumes the loaded register. CoreMark's list and matrix kernels contain many pointer and array dependent loads, and the benchmark bus model often has dmem ready in the same cycle. Recovering those bubbles should improve iterations/cycle without changing the retirement width or adding the broad pipeline stalls that hurt the prior structural M-unit attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline pays a mandatory one-cycle load-use bubble whenever the instruction immediately after a load consumes the loaded register. CoreMark's list and matrix kernels contain many pointer and array dependent loads, and the benchmark bus model often has dmem ready in the same cycle. Recovering those bubbles should improve iterations/cycle without changing the retirement width or adding the broad pipeline stalls that hurt the prior structural M-unit attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a MEM-to-EX load-result bypass path for the specific case where the instruction in EX/MEM is a load, dmem is ready, and the younger ID/EX instruction uses that load's rd. The MEM stage already computes sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally before the MEM/WB register; expose that value and let the forwarding network select it for EX operands when dmem_ready is high. Keep the existing load-use interlock only for dmem stalls or cases where the load data is not yet ready, so correctness and RVFI ordering remain unchanged while ready loads avoid the one-cycle bubble.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"If needed, add a compact forwarding selector encoding for the new MEM-stage load-data bypass while preserving existing pipeline bundle semantics.\"}, {\"file\"...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Correct ID backward-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core pays a two-instruction flush penalty on every taken conditional branch because branches resolve in EX and fetch is effectively static not-taken. CoreMark's inner loops should contain frequent backward taken branches, so recovering even part of that penalty can improve iterations per cycle without touching the already successful M-extension ALU optimization.\\n\\nThe previous predictor attempt identified the right low-cost direction but failed because EX compared against IF fall-through metadata rather than the branch's decoded target, so nominally correct backward predictions still looked wrong. A corrected metadata path is the most promising predictor-only follow-up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core pays a two-instruction flush penalty on every taken conditional branch because branches resolve in EX and fetch is effectively static not-taken. CoreMark's inner loops should contain frequent backward taken branches, so recovering even part of that penalty can improve iterations per cycle without touching the already successful M-extension ALU optimization.\\n\\nThe previous predictor attempt identified the right low-cost direction but failed because EX compared against IF fall-through metadata rather than the branch's decoded target, so nominally correct backward predictions still looked wrong. A corrected metadata path is the most promising predictor-only follow-up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a minimal static predictor that operates after decode: when ID sees a valid conditional branch with a negative B-immediate, redirect fetch to the decoded branch target and mark that branch with predicted_taken and predicted_pc_next in the ID/EX payload. EX then computes the resolved next PC for branches and jumps and redirects only when resolved_pc_next differs from the carried predicted_pc_next.\\n\\nThis keeps th...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Share RV32M divide datapath\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from a narrow ALU micro-optimization: sharing and gating the MUL-family datapath improved Tang Nano Fmax without adding pipeline stalls. The remaining RV32M divide/remainder logic still exposes separate signed and unsigned / and % operators in the combinational ALU case, which can leave yosys with multiple wide divider/remainder cones and extra muxing even though CoreMark mostly executes simpler RV32I operations.\\n\\nPrior attempts to move M-extension work into a multicycle side unit regressed because the added pipeline holds cost more than the Fmax gain. A same-cycle datapath sharing pass keeps the existing timing model and RVFI retirement behavior while attacking the remaining large arithmetic hardware in the common EX block.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from a narrow ALU micro-optimization: sharing and gating the MUL-family datapath improved Tang Nano Fmax without adding pipeline stalls. The remaining RV32M divide/remainder logic still exposes separate signed and unsigned / and % operators in the combinational ALU case, which can leave yosys with multiple wide divider/remainder cones and extra muxing even though CoreMark mostly executes simpler RV32I operations.\\n\\nPrior attempts to move M-extension work into a multicycle side unit regressed because the added pipeline holds cost more than the Fmax gain. A same-cycle datapath sharing pass keeps the existing timing model and RVFI retirement behavior while attacking the remaining large arithmetic hardware in the common EX block.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv so DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU use one shared operand-normalization path, one gated unsigned quotient/remainder datapath, and lightweight sign/zero correction for the four RV32M results. Force divider operands to harmless constants outside divide/remainder ops so non-M ALU operations do not c...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Register fetch-decode boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current core has no real IF/ID pipeline register: the fetched instruction and PC flow combinationally from the PC/imem side into decoder, immediate generation, regfile read addressing, hazard detection, and the ID/EX register. That likely creates a broad timing path through external instruction data and decode fanout, and prior predictor work showed that adding more fetch/decode combinational logic can severely hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core has no real IF/ID pipeline register: the fetched instruction and PC flow combinationally from the PC/imem side into decoder, immediate generation, regfile read addressing, hazard detection, and the ID/EX register. That likely creates a broad timing path through external instruction data and decode fanout, and prior predictor work showed that adding more fetch/decode combinational logic can severely hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the IF/ID boundary into a registered fetch-decode stage, optionally with a one-entry valid/skid behavior for stalls, so imem_data and pc are captured before decode. Preserve the existing single-retire RVFI contract and branch/load-use/dmem stall semantics by flushing or holding the registered IF/ID payload using the same hazard priorities. This should shorten the highest-fanout front-end timing path and improve FPGA Fmax with only a small control change and no new load-data or RV32M critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Keep or minimally adjust the IF/ID bundle so it can represent a registered valid payload and bubble without changing RVFI-visible pipeline metadata.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an IF/ID register or one-entry fetch buffer that captures pc, instruction, and valid, with redirect and flush taking priority over ...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Add tiny fetch BTB predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core still resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken\\ncontrol transfer pays a two-younger-instruction flush. Prior predictor\\nattempts showed that decode-time backward prediction is risky on this FPGA\\nbecause the imem_data-to-decode-to-target-add path can become part of the\\nfetch critical path. A fetch-PC-indexed BTB avoids that failed path while\\nstill targeting CoreMark's hot loop backedges and repeated call/return-like\\nJAL/JALR targets.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core still resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken\\ncontrol transfer pays a two-younger-instruction flush. Prior predictor\\nattempts showed that decode-time backward prediction is risky on this FPGA\\nbecause the imem_data-to-decode-to-target-add path can become part of the\\nfetch critical path. A fetch-PC-indexed BTB avoids that failed path while\\nstill targeting CoreMark's hot loop backedges and repeated call/return-like\\nJAL/JALR targets.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a very small direct-mapped BTB in the fetch stage, indexed only by the\\nregistered PC and updated from EX when a branch or jump resolves. Each entry\\nstores valid, tag, target, and a one-bit or two-bit taken confidence bit;\\nfetch predicts to the stored target only on a tag hit, otherwise it keeps the\\nexisting pc+4 behavior. Carry predicted_pc_next through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX\\nredirects only when the resolved next PC differs from the prediction, and\\nupdate or allocate entries for taken branches/JAL/JALR while weakening or\\nclearing entries on not-taken branches.\\n\\nThis is the most promising predictor-only follow-up because it removes the\\nknown ID predictor critical path, learns actual targets instead of relying on\\na static backward heuristic, and should recover taken-control IPC on stable\\nCoreMark loops with modest LUT/FF cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_p...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Remove regfile reset fanout\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current register file synchronously resets all 32 architectural registers, which forces reset muxing and routing across 1024 state bits. On a small FPGA this can prevent efficient distributed-RAM inference and add reset fanout to a block that is read on the decode critical path.\\n\\nRV32I only requires x0 to read as zero; the other architectural registers do not need a defined hardware reset value as long as software initializes the registers it uses and RVFI reports the actual values read. Removing this reset is a narrow micro-optimization aimed at improving Fmax and possibly LUT pressure without changing pipeline depth, stalls, forwarding, memory behavior, or retirement width.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current register file synchronously resets all 32 architectural registers, which forces reset muxing and routing across 1024 state bits. On a small FPGA this can prevent efficient distributed-RAM inference and add reset fanout to a block that is read on the decode critical path.\\n\\nRV32I only requires x0 to read as zero; the other architectural registers do not need a defined hardware reset value as long as software initializes the registers it uses and RVFI reports the actual values read. Removing this reset is a narrow micro-optimization aimed at improving Fmax and possibly LUT pressure without changing pipeline depth, stalls, forwarding, memory behavior, or retirement width.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/reg_file.sv so reset no longer clears regs[1:31]. Keep x0 hardwired through the existing read and write gating, preserve write-first same-cycle bypass behavior, and leave the write port synchronous.\\n\\nThis should let yosys/nextpnr implement the 32x32 two-read/one-write file with less reset-related muxing and routing, potentially improving the decode/regfile-read timing path and reducing LUT/FF pressure. Because the change only affects ...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Add RAM store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes all younger work whenever a store in EX/MEM sees\\nio_dmemReady low, even though stores do not produce a register result for the\\nfollowing instructions. Under the benchmark's random dmem backpressure model,\\nCoreMark can lose cycles waiting on regular RAM stores that could instead be\\nqueued and drained in order while independent ALU/control work continues.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that changed the M datapath, load-use timing, or the\\nfetch/decode boundary regressed because they lengthened hot combinational paths\\nor inserted broad stalls. A one-entry store buffer is a narrower structural\\nchange: it targets store-only dmem stalls, keeps loads conservative, and avoids\\nnew ALU or branch critical-path logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes all younger work whenever a store in EX/MEM sees\\nio_dmemReady low, even though stores do not produce a register result for the\\nfollowing instructions. Under the benchmark's random dmem backpressure model,\\nCoreMark can lose cycles waiting on regular RAM stores that could instead be\\nqueued and drained in order while independent ALU/control work continues.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that changed the M datapath, load-use timing, or the\\nfetch/decode boundary regressed because they lengthened hot combinational paths\\nor inserted broad stalls. A one-entry store buffer is a narrower structural\\nchange: it targets store-only dmem stalls, keeps loads conservative, and avoids\\nnew ALU or branch critical-path logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry in-order store buffer for normal RAM stores only. When a\\nnon-MMIO store reaches MEM and the buffer is empty, capture its address, data,\\nmask, and RVFI memory metadata, allow the store instruction to retire, and let\\nthe buffer continue driving dmem_wen until io_dmemReady accepts it. Stall on\\nloads, MMIO stores, misali...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Predict JAL in decode\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken control transfer in EX, so unconditional\\nJAL instructions pay the same two-younger-instruction flush penalty as taken\\nconditional branches. Prior predictor attempts showed that conditional\\nbackward prediction lengthened the imem/decode/target path and that mutable\\nBTB arrays complicated formal convergence, so the next predictor experiment\\nshould target a smaller, deterministic subset of control flow.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken control transfer in EX, so unconditional\\nJAL instructions pay the same two-younger-instruction flush penalty as taken\\nconditional branches. Prior predictor attempts showed that conditional\\nbackward prediction lengthened the imem/decode/target path and that mutable\\nBTB arrays complicated formal convergence, so the next predictor experiment\\nshould target a smaller, deterministic subset of control flow.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a static early predictor only for valid JAL instructions in the decode\\nstage. JAL is always taken and its target is encoded in the instruction, so ID\\ncan compute pc+J-immediate and redirect fetch one cycle earlier without any\\ndynamic predictor state, branch comparison, or BTB tag lookup. Carry a\\npredicted_pc_next bit/value through ID/EX and EX/MEM so EX suppresses the\\nnormal redirect when the resolved JAL target matches the decode prediction,\\nwhile branches and JALR keep the existing EX-resolution behavior.\\n\\nThis should recover some CoreMark IPC on function-call and unconditional-jump\\npaths while avoiding the two known predictor hazards: conditional decode\\nprediction on every branch and mutable fetch-side predictor arrays. The change\\nis intentionally narrow and should be easier for riscv-formal than a BTB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"des...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Gate EX control-transfer datapath\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage computes branch comparisons, branch targets, and JALR target sums for every instruction, even though CoreMark's hot path is dominated by ordinary ALU and memory operations. Prior results show that narrow gating of always-live datapaths can improve Tang Nano Fmax, while larger structural or predictor changes have repeatedly lost more timing than they recovered in IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage computes branch comparisons, branch targets, and JALR target sums for every instruction, even though CoreMark's hot path is dominated by ordinary ALU and memory operations. Prior results show that narrow gating of always-live datapaths can improve Tang Nano Fmax, while larger structural or predictor changes have repeatedly lost more timing than they recovered in IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv so control-transfer hardware is only active for actual branch or jump instructions. Gate the branch comparator operands when is_branch is false, compute only the selected branch comparison for the decoded branch_op, and feed harmless constants into the branch-target and JALR-target adders when their instruction class is not active. Preserve the existing EX-stage resolution point, misalignment trap behavior, RVFI pc_next reporting, and redirect semantics.\\n\\nThis should reduce EX-stage LUT/routing pressure and remove always-live comparator/adder cones from common RV32I ALU and load/store cycles without adding state, stalls, or front-end prediction metadata. The expected gain is primarily Fmax, with essentially no IPC downside because pipeline timing and retirement behavior remain unchanged.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate branch comparator inputs and control-target adders so non-control instructions do not k...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Precompute PC targets in decode\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage resolves branches and jumps while also running the ALU,\\nforwarding muxes, branch comparators, and RVFI next-PC construction. Prior\\nstructural attempts that added pipeline latency, broad stalls, or early\\nfront-end redirects regressed, so the next structural experiment should be a\\npure retiming that shortens EX without changing prediction policy or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage resolves branches and jumps while also running the ALU,\\nforwarding muxes, branch comparators, and RVFI next-PC construction. Prior\\nstructural attempts that added pipeline latency, broad stalls, or early\\nfront-end redirects regressed, so the next structural experiment should be a\\npure retiming that shortens EX without changing prediction policy or IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Compute PC+4 and the PC-relative target PC+imm in ID and store them in the\\nexisting ID/EX pipeline register. EX can then use the precomputed PC+imm for\\nconditional branch targets, JAL targets, and AUIPC results, and use the\\nprecomputed PC+4 for fall-through, JAL/JALR link data, and RVFI pc_wdata.\\n\\nThis removes duplicated 32-bit PC adders from the EX control path and lowers\\nfanout around branch/jump resolution while preserving the same five-stage\\ntiming, load-use behavior, RVFI order, and single-channel nret=1 contract.\\nUnlike the failed decode-prediction attempts, the ID-side target add feeds\\nonly a register and never drives the fetch PC in the same cycle, so it should\\navoid creating a new imem_data-to-PC critical loop.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend id_ex_t with registered pc_plus4 and pc_imm_target fields used by EX for branch, JAL, AUIPC, and RVFI next-PC construction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute pc+4 and pc+imm f...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"One-entry JALR return predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing core resolves JALR in EX, so every function return pays the same two-younger-instruction flush as a taken branch. Prior predictor attempts lost fitness or broke formal because they added decode-time target generation on the imem critical path or introduced a general mutable BTB array. A much narrower predictor can target repeated return PCs without touching conditional branches or adding a broad fetch/decode target path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing core resolves JALR in EX, so every function return pays the same two-younger-instruction flush as a taken branch. Prior predictor attempts lost fitness or broke formal because they added decode-time target generation on the imem critical path or introduced a general mutable BTB array. A much narrower predictor can target repeated return PCs without touching conditional branches or adding a broad fetch/decode target path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single scalar JALR target cache in fetch, updated only when EX resolves a legal JALR. The cache stores one valid bit, one PC tag, and one resolved target; when the current fetch PC matches the tag, IF predicts the cached target as the next PC and carries predicted_pc_next metadata through ID/EX. EX compares the resolved next PC against the carried prediction and redirects only on mismatch, while all branches, JAL, and cache misses keep the current pc+4/static-not-taken behavior.\\n\\nThis is deliberately smaller than the failed BTB attempt: no predictor array, no counters, no conditional-branch update policy, and no imem_data-to-immediate-to-PC combinational redirect. It should recover recurring CoreMark return penalties after warm-up with limited LUT/FF cost and lower formal risk than a general fetch BTB.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add pre...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Gate divider operands only\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already benefited strongly from isolating the MUL-family datapath from ordinary RV32I ALU operations. The remaining DIV/REM operators still consume the live ALU operands directly, so yosys may keep wide divider/remainder cones and routing coupled to the EX-stage result mux even when CoreMark is mostly executing adds, compares, loads, stores, and branches.\\n\\nA prior attempt to share the divider datapath regressed because it introduced signed normalization, restore muxing, and simultaneous quotient/remainder logic. The safer micro-optimization is to avoid that structural rewrite and only gate the raw divider operands outside actual DIV/REM operations.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already benefited strongly from isolating the MUL-family datapath from ordinary RV32I ALU operations. The remaining DIV/REM operators still consume the live ALU operands directly, so yosys may keep wide divider/remainder cones and routing coupled to the EX-stage result mux even when CoreMark is mostly executing adds, compares, loads, stores, and branches.\\n\\nA prior attempt to share the divider datapath regressed because it introduced signed normalization, restore muxing, and simultaneous quotient/remainder logic. The safer micro-optimization is to avoid that structural rewrite and only gate the raw divider operands outside actual DIV/REM operations.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an is_divrem_op decode inside rtl/alu.sv and feed the real a/b operands to division and remainder operators only for ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, and ALU_REMU. For all other ALU ops, drive the divider operand wires with harmless constants, then use those gated wires in the existing RV32M divide-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 cases.\\n\\nThis keeps the pipeline single-cycle, preserves RV32M and RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS semantics, and avoids the failed normalization/shari...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Add fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The benchmark model injects independent instruction and data bus stalls, and the current pipeline freezes fetch whenever a data-memory operation is held in EX/MEM. If instruction memory is ready during that backend hold, the core wastes an opportunity to capture the next sequential instruction and can then immediately lose more cycles to a later imem stall after dmem unblocks.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that always inserted an IF/ID register or added store-buffer control regressed, so this hypothesis keeps the normal zero-wait path combinational and only adds a one-entry skid slot for cycles where the backend is already unable to advance.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The benchmark model injects independent instruction and data bus stalls, and the current pipeline freezes fetch whenever a data-memory operation is held in EX/MEM. If instruction memory is ready during that backend hold, the core wastes an opportunity to capture the next sequential instruction and can then immediately lose more cycles to a later imem stall after dmem unblocks.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that always inserted an IF/ID register or added store-buffer control regressed, so this hypothesis keeps the normal zero-wait path combinational and only adds a one-entry skid slot for cycles where the backend is already unable to advance.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry fetch skid buffer in the IF stage that captures the current imem instruction and PC when dmem_stall holds ID/EX and EX/MEM but imemReady is high. When the backend releases, feed the buffered instruction to ID before requesting/advancing to the next PC; invalidate the buffer on any EX redirect so wrong-path contents never retire.\\n\\nThis should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle under the random stall model by overlapping useful instruction fetch with data-memory wait cycles, without changing retirement width, branch resol...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Add loop-target prefetch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing core still pays a taken-control penalty, but prior predictor\\nattempts show that decode-time redirects and mutable BTB-style PC metadata\\ncan lose more Fmax or formal convergence than they recover in IPC. CoreMark\\nnevertheless has tight repeated loops, and the random imem backpressure model\\nmakes avoiding wrong-path fetch work valuable if the predictor can stay off\\nthe critical PC-update path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing core still pays a taken-control penalty, but prior predictor\\nattempts show that decode-time redirects and mutable BTB-style PC metadata\\ncan lose more Fmax or formal convergence than they recover in IPC. CoreMark\\nnevertheless has tight repeated loops, and the random imem backpressure model\\nmakes avoiding wrong-path fetch work valuable if the predictor can stay off\\nthe critical PC-update path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny one-entry loop-target prefetch predictor that learns only resolved\\ntaken backward conditional branches in EX, storing the branch PC and target in\\nflops. Fetch keeps the architecturally visible PC policy unchanged until a\\nregistered PC tag hit is observed, then uses the stored target as the next PC\\nand carries a predicted_pc_next value with that fetched instruction so EX can\\nsuppress the normal redirect only when the resolved next PC exactly matches.\\n\\nThis is deliberately narrower than the failed BTB and decode predictors: no\\npredictor array, no instruction-decode-to-PC immediate path, no JAL/JALR\\ntarget speculation, and no change to branch condition resolution. It should\\nrecover the hottest loop backedge penalties after warm-up while limiting Fmax\\nrisk to a single PC comparator and target mux driven by registered predictor\\nstate.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add compact...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Trim dead pipeline metadata\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core has already benefited from narrow datapath cleanup, while later attempts to add gating, prediction, buffering, or divider rewrites mostly lost Fmax or broke formal. There are still dead bits carried through hot pipeline bundles: ctrl.is_lui is decoded but never consumed, and EX/MEM branch_taken/branch_target are written but not read by MEM, WB, RVFI, hazard, or forwarding logic. On a small FPGA these unused flops and their assignment cones can still consume routing, reset/load muxing, and placement freedom.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core has already benefited from narrow datapath cleanup, while later attempts to add gating, prediction, buffering, or divider rewrites mostly lost Fmax or broke formal. There are still dead bits carried through hot pipeline bundles: ctrl.is_lui is decoded but never consumed, and EX/MEM branch_taken/branch_target are written but not read by MEM, WB, RVFI, hazard, or forwarding logic. On a small FPGA these unused flops and their assignment cones can still consume routing, reset/load muxing, and placement freedom.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove unused pipeline metadata instead of adding new behavior. Delete ctrl_t.is_lui and its decoder/id_stage assignments, and delete ex_mem_t.branch_taken and ex_mem_t.branch_target plus the corresponding ex_stage register writes. LUI behavior is already represented by ALU_LUI with alu_src/reg_write, branch redirects use the combinational EX outputs, and RVFI pc_next uses the resolved value already stored in EX/MEM, so these fields should not affect architectural state or retirement.\\n\\nThis is a pure micro-optimization: fewer registered bits, less control fanout, and less unnecessary mux/load/reset logic in the ID/EX and EX/MEM registers. The expected gain is modest but safer than another arithmetic or predictor change because it does not change pipelin...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Bypass ALU for memory addresses\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage routes load and store effective-address generation through\\nthe same combinational ALU result mux used for arithmetic, branches, jumps,\\nand RV32M operations. CoreMark executes many memory operations, so their MEM\\naddress path can inherit unnecessary muxing and arithmetic fanout even though\\nthe required operation is only rs1 + immediate.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added front-end state, store queues, or load\\nbypasses regressed because they added control complexity or new critical\\npaths. A narrower structural split inside EX keeps the pipeline timing and IPC\\nidentical while trying to shorten a hot address-generation path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage routes load and store effective-address generation through\\nthe same combinational ALU result mux used for arithmetic, branches, jumps,\\nand RV32M operations. CoreMark executes many memory operations, so their MEM\\naddress path can inherit unnecessary muxing and arithmetic fanout even though\\nthe required operation is only rs1 + immediate.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added front-end state, store queues, or load\\nbypasses regressed because they added control complexity or new critical\\npaths. A narrower structural split inside EX keeps the pipeline timing and IPC\\nidentical while trying to shorten a hot address-generation path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated simple effective-address adder in rtl/ex_stage.sv for\\nload/store instructions, fed by the existing forwarded rs1 value and the\\nregistered immediate. When mem_read or mem_write is set, capture this adder's\\nresult into ex_mem.alu_result instead of the general ALU output; all other\\ninstructions keep the existing ALU, branch, jump, AUIPC, and RVFI behavior.\\n\\nThis should let synthesis keep memory address generation out of the wider ALU\\nresult cone that also contains M-extension and c...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Cache repeated JAL targets\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The core still pays a two-younger-instruction flush for every taken control\\ntransfer. Prior predictor attempts show that decode-time target generation,\\nconditional branch prediction, and general mutable BTBs tend to lose FPGA\\ntiming or formal convergence. A narrower predictor should target only a\\ndeterministic, always-taken control-flow class while keeping instruction\\ndecode and branch comparison out of the fetch PC critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The core still pays a two-younger-instruction flush for every taken control\\ntransfer. Prior predictor attempts show that decode-time target generation,\\nconditional branch prediction, and general mutable BTBs tend to lose FPGA\\ntiming or formal convergence. A narrower predictor should target only a\\ndeterministic, always-taken control-flow class while keeping instruction\\ndecode and branch comparison out of the fetch PC critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry fetch-side target cache for repeated JAL PCs. The entry is\\nupdated in EX when a legal JAL resolves, storing valid, the JAL PC tag, and\\nits already-computed pc_imm_target. Fetch compares only the registered PC\\nagainst this one tag; on a hit it uses the stored target as the next PC and\\ncarries predicted_pc_next metadata with that instruction so EX can suppress\\nthe normal JAL redirect only when the resolved next PC exactly matches.\\n\\nThis differs from the failed JAL decode predictor by avoiding any\\nimem_data-to-immediate-to-PC combinational path, and differs from the failed\\nBTB by avoiding arrays, counters, conditional branches, and JALR targets.\\nIt should recover repeated unconditional jump penalties in CoreMark with a\\nsmall amount of registered state and a single PC compare/mux.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicte...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Mux load byte lanes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current MEM stage extracts byte and halfword loads with a variable right\\nshift by addr[1:0] * 8. CoreMark has frequent loads, and on the Tang Nano 20K\\nthat small barrel-shifter style cone may sit on the dmem_rdata-to-MEM/WB path\\nand consume more LUT/routing than a direct byte-lane mux.\\n\\nRecent micro-opt attempts that added operand gating, divider rewrites, or\\npipeline metadata churn regressed, so the most promising next angle is a\\nbehavior-preserving local simplification of an existing hot datapath rather\\nthan adding new control or state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current MEM stage extracts byte and halfword loads with a variable right\\nshift by addr[1:0] * 8. CoreMark has frequent loads, and on the Tang Nano 20K\\nthat small barrel-shifter style cone may sit on the dmem_rdata-to-MEM/WB path\\nand consume more LUT/routing than a direct byte-lane mux.\\n\\nRecent micro-opt attempts that added operand gating, divider rewrites, or\\npipeline metadata churn regressed, so the most promising next angle is a\\nbehavior-preserving local simplification of an existing hot datapath rather\\nthan adding new control or state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/mem_stage.sv so load extraction uses explicit case statements\\nover in.alu_result[1:0] to select byte_val and hword_val from dmem_rdata,\\ninstead of computing shifted = dmem_rdata >> (in.alu_result[1:0] * 8).\\nKeep the existing sign/zero extension, misalignment trapping, byte masks,\\ndmem port behavior, and RVFI memory fields unchanged.\\n\\nThis should reduce LUT depth and routing in the load-data path without\\nchanging pipeline timing, stalls, retirement order, or the nret=1 RVFI port\\ncontract. The expected gain is modest Fmax improvement with essentially no\\nIPC downside.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Repla...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Qualify load-use interlock sources\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 fields of the following instruction, even when the following opcode does not actually read one of those fields. That can inject unnecessary bubbles after loads in CoreMark's pointer-heavy code, reducing iterations/cycle without improving correctness.\\n\\nA prior attempt at source qualification broke because it used opcode-level approximations and changed ID/EX operand metadata. The safer structural version is to add exact decoder-produced source-use bits and use them only in the hazard decision, leaving RVFI rs addresses/data and the existing forwarding metadata unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 fields of the following instruction, even when the following opcode does not actually read one of those fields. That can inject unnecessary bubbles after loads in CoreMark's pointer-heavy code, reducing iterations/cycle without improving correctness.\\n\\nA prior attempt at source qualification broke because it used opcode-level approximations and changed ID/EX operand metadata. The safer structural version is to add exact decoder-produced source-use bits and use them only in the hazard decision, leaving RVFI rs addresses/data and the existing forwarding metadata unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extend the decoder/control path with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 bits that are cleared only for instruction forms that architecturally do not read the corresponding register field. Feed those bits for the current IF/ID instruction into hazard_unit, and gate the load-use comparisons so a load only stalls when the younger instruction truly consumes the loaded rd.\\n\\nThis should recover occasional false load-use bubbles for OP-IMM, LOAD, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK-like instructions while p...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Predict returns with tiny RAS\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing core still resolves every JALR in EX, so function returns pay the normal taken-control flush penalty. Prior predictor attempts lost fitness when they added decode-time immediate target generation, fetch-side BTB/tag arrays, or broad predicted-PC metadata for many control-flow classes. CoreMark still has repeated call/return structure, so a narrower return-only predictor may recover useful IPC with less timing cost than general branch or JAL target prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing core still resolves every JALR in EX, so function returns pay the normal taken-control flush penalty. Prior predictor attempts lost fitness when they added decode-time immediate target generation, fetch-side BTB/tag arrays, or broad predicted-PC metadata for many control-flow classes. CoreMark still has repeated call/return structure, so a narrower return-only predictor may recover useful IPC with less timing cost than general branch or JAL target prediction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny return-address stack predictor for canonical returns only. When EX retires or resolves a legal JAL that writes x1 or x5, push the already-available pc_plus4 link address into a 2-entry RAS; when decode sees a valid JALR with rs1=x1 or x5, rd=x0, and imm=0, redirect fetch to the registered RAS top one cycle before EX would otherwise resolve it. Carry predicted_pc_next and predicted_valid for that instruction through ID/EX, and in EX suppress the normal JALR redirect only if the computed target exactly matches the carried prediction; otherwise redirect to the resolved target and repair or invalidate the RAS entry.\\n\\nThis differs from the failed JAL decode predictor because there is no imem_data-to-J-immediate-adder-to-PC path, and differs from the failed JALR target cache because returns use call-pushed link addresses rather than a fetch PC target cache. Th...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Trim pipeline reset muxes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The best successful changes for this core have been narrow timing and routing cleanups that preserve the five-stage behavior, while recent predictor, buffer, divider, and metadata edits mostly regressed. The current pipeline still resets entire packed ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB records, adding reset muxing and fanout to many datapath bits whose values are architecturally ignored whenever valid is low.\\n\\nUnlike removing reset from the architectural register file, trimming reset on invalid pipeline payload fields should not expose software-visible state. It targets placement and Fmax pressure in stage registers without changing IPC, branch policy, memory timing, RVFI order, or the nret=1 interface.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best successful changes for this core have been narrow timing and routing cleanups that preserve the five-stage behavior, while recent predictor, buffer, divider, and metadata edits mostly regressed. The current pipeline still resets entire packed ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB records, adding reset muxing and fanout to many datapath bits whose values are architecturally ignored whenever valid is low.\\n\\nUnlike removing reset from the architectural register file, trimming reset on invalid pipeline payload fields should not expose software-visible state. It targets placement and Fmax pressure in stage registers without changing IPC, branch policy, memory timing, RVFI order, or the nret=1 interface.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor the pipeline stage registers so reset clears the valid bits and the small set of side-effecting control bits that can drive writes, memory requests, traps, or hazard decisions, while non-side-effect payload fields are either left unchanged or only written on normal captures. Keep MEM/WB and top-level RVFI outputs deterministic by ensuring invalid retirements report valid=0 and no register or memory side effects, ...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Register writeback result\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current MEM/WB stage carries both alu_result and read_data, then the WB\\nstage selects the final writeback value combinationally every cycle. That\\nselected value feeds the regfile write port, MEM/WB forwarding into EX, and\\nRVFI rd_wdata, so the small load-vs-ALU mux sits on several timing-relevant\\nfanout paths even though its decision is already known when MEM/WB captures.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added front-end state, prediction metadata,\\nstore buffering, or same-cycle load bypasses regressed by lengthening hotter\\npaths or changing stall behavior. This is a narrower pipeline retiming that\\nshould preserve IPC exactly while shortening writeback and forwarding logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current MEM/WB stage carries both alu_result and read_data, then the WB\\nstage selects the final writeback value combinationally every cycle. That\\nselected value feeds the regfile write port, MEM/WB forwarding into EX, and\\nRVFI rd_wdata, so the small load-vs-ALU mux sits on several timing-relevant\\nfanout paths even though its decision is already known when MEM/WB captures.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added front-end state, prediction metadata,\\nstore buffering, or same-cycle load bypasses regressed by lengthening hotter\\npaths or changing stall behavior. This is a narrower pipeline retiming that\\nshould preserve IPC exactly while shortening writeback and forwarding logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a registered wb_data field to the MEM/WB bundle and compute it inside\\nmem_stage at the same time read_data is formed. For loads, wb_data captures\\nthe sign/zero-extended load data; for all other writeback instructions it\\ncaptures the EX/MEM alu_result. Then simplify wb_stage so w_data is just the\\nregistered wb_data field, and keep RVFI rd_wdata using that same value.\\n\\nThis should remove the live MEM/WB mem_to_reg mux from the regfile w...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"One-bit loop prediction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core still pays the full EX redirect flush on every taken conditional branch, but prior predictor attempts show that decode redirects, BTB arrays, JAL/JALR target caches, and 32-bit predicted-PC metadata all cost more FPGA fitness than they recover. CoreMark still has hot loop backedges, so the remaining predictor opportunity is to make the predictor narrower rather than more capable.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core still pays the full EX redirect flush on every taken conditional branch, but prior predictor attempts show that decode redirects, BTB arrays, JAL/JALR target caches, and 32-bit predicted-PC metadata all cost more FPGA fitness than they recover. CoreMark still has hot loop backedges, so the remaining predictor opportunity is to make the predictor narrower rather than more capable.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry taken-branch target predictor for resolved backward conditional branches only. Fetch compares the registered PC against one learned branch PC tag and, on a hit, uses the stored target as the next PC while carrying only a one-bit predicted_taken flag with that instruction. EX suppresses the normal taken-branch redirect when the branch was predicted taken and actually resolves taken; on a predicted-taken branch that resolves not-taken, EX redirects to the already-registered fall-through pc_plus4 and clears or weakens the entry.\\n\\nThis intentionally avoids the failed ingredients from earlier predictor attempts: no decode-time immediate-to-PC path, no predictor array, no JAL/JALR/return prediction, and no 32-bit predicted_pc_next comparison through the pipeline. The cost is one PC tag compare, one target mux, one learned target register, and a single metadata bit, which may recover repeated loop-backedge flushes with less Fmax damage than previous predictor designs.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Qualify EX/MEM forwarding\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The forwarding unit currently gives EX/MEM priority for any instruction with reg_write set, including loads. A load's architectural writeback value is not available in EX/MEM; the existing load-use interlock ensures consumers only execute once the load has reached MEM/WB. Keeping loads in the EX/MEM forwarding match therefore leaves dead compare/select logic on the EX operand path and can momentarily select an unusable load address during held bubbles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The forwarding unit currently gives EX/MEM priority for any instruction with reg_write set, including loads. A load's architectural writeback value is not available in EX/MEM; the existing load-use interlock ensures consumers only execute once the load has reached MEM/WB. Keeping loads in the EX/MEM forwarding match therefore leaves dead compare/select logic on the EX operand path and can momentarily select an unusable load address during held bubbles.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Qualify the EX/MEM bypass path so it is only eligible for results that are actually available in EX/MEM: ALU, LUI/AUIPC, and JAL/JALR link values. Pass a compact non-load indicator, or mem_to_reg/mem_read, from core.sv into forward_unit and add it to the EX/MEM priority condition for both rs1 and rs2.\\n\\nThis preserves all pipeline timing, RVFI metadata, load-use stalls, and MEM/WB load forwarding, but removes an impossible bypass case from the highest-priority forwarding path. The expected benefit is modest Fmax improvement from simpler EX operand select logic with essentially no IPC downside.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/forward_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an EX/MEM bypass-eligible input and require it in the rs1/rs2 EX/MEM forwarding priority checks so loads are never selected from the unavailable EX/MEM address result.\"}, {\"file\": \"rt...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Multicycle divider only\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already gained most of its Fmax by sharing the MUL-family datapath, but DIV/REM still live as full combinational operators inside the normal ALU result mux. Prior attempts show that moving all RV32M work into a side unit regresses because CoreMark uses multiply enough that broad M stalls are costly, and operand gating alone does not remove the divider cones from synthesis.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should target only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. These operations are rare in the timed CoreMark hot path compared with adds, loads, stores, branches, and multiplies, so paying multicycle latency for divider-class instructions is likely cheaper than carrying same-cycle divide/remainder hardware on every EX-stage timing path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already gained most of its Fmax by sharing the MUL-family datapath, but DIV/REM still live as full combinational operators inside the normal ALU result mux. Prior attempts show that moving all RV32M work into a side unit regresses because CoreMark uses multiply enough that broad M stalls are costly, and operand gating alone does not remove the divider cones from synthesis.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should target only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. These operations are rare in the timed CoreMark hot path compared with adds, loads, stores, branches, and multiplies, so paying multicycle latency for divider-class instructions is likely cheaper than carrying same-cycle divide/remainder hardware on every EX-stage timing path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the ALU's real DIV/REM combinational operators with a dedicated iterative divider/remainder unit that is invoked only when an ALU_DIV, ALU_DIVU, ALU_REM, or ALU_REMU instruction reaches EX. Keep RV32I operations and the successful shared MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU datapath single-cycle in the existing ALU.\\n\\nOn a divider instruction, hold IF...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Predict only recently taken branch\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The core still pays a two-younger-instruction flush on every taken branch,\\nbut every previous predictor that decoded instructions in the fetch path,\\nadded general BTB/RAS structures, or carried wide predicted-PC metadata has\\nregressed on Tang Nano timing. The remaining plausible predictor angle is a\\nvery small learned branch fast path that avoids imem_data-to-PC logic and\\navoids predicting jumps or returns.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The core still pays a two-younger-instruction flush on every taken branch,\\nbut every previous predictor that decoded instructions in the fetch path,\\nadded general BTB/RAS structures, or carried wide predicted-PC metadata has\\nregressed on Tang Nano timing. The remaining plausible predictor angle is a\\nvery small learned branch fast path that avoids imem_data-to-PC logic and\\navoids predicting jumps or returns.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry EX-trained conditional-branch predictor that stores only\\nthe most recently resolved taken backward branch PC and target. IF compares\\nthe registered PC against this one tag and, on a hit, selects the registered\\ntarget as next_pc while tagging the fetched instruction with a one-bit\\npredicted_taken flag. EX suppresses the normal redirect only when that same\\nbranch resolves taken; if it resolves not-taken or the instruction is not a\\nmatching branch, EX redirects to the already-registered pc_plus4 and clears\\nthe entry.\\n\\nThis is intentionally narrower than the failed loop predictor: no immediate\\ndecode in IF, no arrays or counters, no JAL/JALR/RAS prediction, and no\\n32-bit predicted_pc_next pipeline comparison. It targets only stable CoreMark\\nloop backedges and accepts low upside in exchange for minimal predictor cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one-bit...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Gate shift operand path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best result came from a narrow ALU cleanup that kept the pipeline unchanged while reducing always-live arithmetic hardware around common RV32I operations. Most later attempts regressed when they added control/state, altered forwarding, or rewrote divider and branch paths. The remaining safer micro-opt target is the ALU shift cone: SLL/SRL/SRA are relatively infrequent in CoreMark, but the live shifter still shares the EX result mux and operand routing with adds, compares, branches, and memory address generation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best result came from a narrow ALU cleanup that kept the pipeline unchanged while reducing always-live arithmetic hardware around common RV32I operations. Most later attempts regressed when they added control/state, altered forwarding, or rewrote divider and branch paths. The remaining safer micro-opt target is the ALU shift cone: SLL/SRL/SRA are relatively infrequent in CoreMark, but the live shifter still shares the EX result mux and operand routing with adds, compares, branches, and memory address generation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/alu.sv so shift operations use a small is_shift_op predicate and gated shift operands. Feed the real a operand and b[4:0] shamt only for ALU_SLL, ALU_SRL, and ALU_SRA; otherwise drive the shifter inputs with constants and use those gated wires in the existing shift case arms. Keep all ALU op encodings, RV32M behavior, RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions, and single-cycle pipeline timing unchanged.\\n\\nThis should reduce switching, LUT input pressure, and routing from the barrel-shift cone into the common EX-stage ALU result path without adding any new state, stalls, predictor metadata, memory behavior, or RVFI-visible changes. The expected upside is modest but it follows the one proven pattern for this core: isolate a rarely used ALU sub-datapath while prese...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Split M arithmetic sidecar\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The successful current best isolated the MUL-family datapath inside the ALU, but the EX-stage result mux still mixes ordinary RV32I operations, memory address generation, branch support, multiply, and divide/remainder in one large combinational block. Prior structural attempts that added stalls, predictors, fetch buffers, or broad pipeline retiming mostly regressed, so the next structural angle should preserve the existing five-stage timing and IPC while giving synthesis a cleaner separation between the hot RV32I path and rarely used M-extension hardware.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The successful current best isolated the MUL-family datapath inside the ALU, but the EX-stage result mux still mixes ordinary RV32I operations, memory address generation, branch support, multiply, and divide/remainder in one large combinational block. Prior structural attempts that added stalls, predictors, fetch buffers, or broad pipeline retiming mostly regressed, so the next structural angle should preserve the existing five-stage timing and IPC while giving synthesis a cleaner separation between the hot RV32I path and rarely used M-extension hardware.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the current monolithic ALU into a small RV32I fast ALU plus a separate combinational RV32M sidecar module. The fast ALU handles ADD/SUB/logical/compare/shift/LUI and remains the default source for CoreMark's common arithmetic, branch compare operands, and load/store address generation. The M sidecar receives gated operands only for MUL/DIV/REM opcodes and returns an M result that is selected at the final EX result mux when the decoded op is an M instruction.\\n\\nThis is intentionally not a multicycle M-unit: it preserves single-cycle retirement behavior, forwarding, load-use handling, RVFI metadata, and the nret=1 interface. The expected benefit is mostly Fmax and routing quality from reducing fa...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Carry exact loop prediction metadata\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The core still pays a two-instruction flush on taken loop backedges, but prior predictor attempts show that decode-time redirects, BTB arrays, JAL/JALR caches, and live predictor rechecks usually cost more timing or break RVFI pc_fwd. The least-bad predictor opportunity is still an EX-trained single-entry loop predictor, provided the predicted target used for redirect suppression is carried with the fetched instruction instead of reread from mutable predictor state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The core still pays a two-instruction flush on taken loop backedges, but prior predictor attempts show that decode-time redirects, BTB arrays, JAL/JALR caches, and live predictor rechecks usually cost more timing or break RVFI pc_fwd. The least-bad predictor opportunity is still an EX-trained single-entry loop predictor, provided the predicted target used for redirect suppression is carried with the fetched instruction instead of reread from mutable predictor state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry predictor for resolved taken backward conditional branches only. IF compares the registered fetch PC against a single registered tag and, on a hit, uses the registered target as next PC while storing predicted_valid, predicted_pc, and predicted_target in the IF/ID and ID/EX payload for that exact instruction. EX suppresses the normal taken-branch redirect only when the retiring branch's carried predicted_valid is set, the carried predicted_pc matches its PC, and the carried predicted_target exactly equals the resolved target; otherwise EX redirects to the resolved next PC and updates or clears the predictor.\\n\\nThis keeps instruction decode out of the fetch PC path, avoids arrays/counters/JAL/JALR/RAS speculation, and directly addresses the latest broken predictor lesson by never consulting live predictor state for RVFI pc_next validation. The expected up...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Drop dead AUIPC ALU mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already precomputes PC+imm in ID and uses that registered value for AUIPC writeback in EX. However, the EX ALU input path still contains an is_auipc-controlled mux that forces alu_a to zero even though the ALU result is ignored for AUIPC. That mux adds control fanout and operand routing to the common ALU path used by arithmetic, load/store address generation, and branch support.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best bench core already precomputes PC+imm in ID and uses that registered value for AUIPC writeback in EX. However, the EX ALU input path still contains an is_auipc-controlled mux that forces alu_a to zero even though the ALU result is ignored for AUIPC. That mux adds control fanout and operand routing to the common ALU path used by arithmetic, load/store address generation, and branch support.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the AUIPC special case from the ALU operand-a selection in rtl/ex_stage.sv, leaving alu_a equal to the forwarded rs1 value for all instructions. AUIPC architectural behavior remains unchanged because ex_mem.alu_result already selects the registered pc_imm_target when ctrl.is_auipc is set, and RVFI pc/data metadata continues to flow through the existing pipeline registers.\\n\\nThis is a small Fmax-oriented cleanup that removes one unnecessary 32-bit mux from the hot EX operand path without adding state, changing stalls, touching RV32M arithmetic, altering prediction, or modifying the nret=1 RVFI contract. The expected gain is modest but the risk is lower than prior gating attempts because it deletes dead logic instead of adding new op-dependent gating.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the ctrl.is_auipc mux from alu_a selection because AUIPC writeback already uses the registered pc_imm_target inste...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Clean divider EX handshake\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core still carries full combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\noperators in the ALU result cone, while the successful multiply sharing pass\\nalready removed much of the always-live M-extension pressure. Prior broad\\nmulticycle M-unit attempts regressed or broke because they stalled common\\nmultiply operations and used ad hoc control that desynchronized EX/MEM and\\nRVFI payloads. A divider-only structural split remains attractive if the EX\\nstage owns a precise valid/hold/done handshake and captures the entire\\ninstruction payload atomically with the divider result.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core still carries full combinational DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\noperators in the ALU result cone, while the successful multiply sharing pass\\nalready removed much of the always-live M-extension pressure. Prior broad\\nmulticycle M-unit attempts regressed or broke because they stalled common\\nmultiply operations and used ad hoc control that desynchronized EX/MEM and\\nRVFI payloads. A divider-only structural split remains attractive if the EX\\nstage owns a precise valid/hold/done handshake and captures the entire\\ninstruction payload atomically with the divider result.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace only the real DIV/REM combinational datapath with an iterative or\\nstaged divider unit that starts when a valid divider-class instruction enters\\nEX. While the divider is busy, hold PC, ID/EX, and the in-flight EX payload;\\ndo not bubble EX/MEM with partial metadata. When done, commit exactly one\\nEX/MEM register update containing the original instruction metadata,\\nforwarded rs values, pc_next, control bits, and the final quotient or\\nremainder. Keep RV32I and the existing shared multiply family single-cycle.\\n\\nThis should improve Fmax by removing the remaining same-cycle divide and\\nremainder cones from the hot ALU path, with limited CoreMark IPC co...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Cache redirect target instruction\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Previous predictor attempts for this core mostly regressed because they put tag compares, target muxes, decode immediates, or predicted-PC metadata on the fetch PC path, and the latest loop predictor broke when prediction state was consulted at the wrong time. The remaining predictor opportunity is to avoid early PC speculation entirely while still reducing the penalty of repeated taken CoreMark loop backedges.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Previous predictor attempts for this core mostly regressed because they put tag compares, target muxes, decode immediates, or predicted-PC metadata on the fetch PC path, and the latest loop predictor broke when prediction state was consulted at the wrong time. The remaining predictor opportunity is to avoid early PC speculation entirely while still reducing the penalty of repeated taken CoreMark loop backedges.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry redirect target instruction cache trained only by resolved taken backward conditional branches. When such a branch redirects to a target and the target instruction is subsequently fetched with imemReady, remember the branch PC, target PC, and first target instruction. On a later occurrence of the same branch resolving taken in EX, do not predict the PC before resolution; instead, use the cached target instruction as the IF/ID payload in the redirect cycle and set the real PC to the target for the following sequential fetch.\\n\\nThis should recover one front-end bubble on hot loop backedges without adding a speculative next-PC mux to normal fetch, without suppressing EX redirects, and without carrying mutable predicted_pc_next metadata through RVFI. Mismatches, not-taken exits, imem stalls, or non-matching branches simply fall back to the current redirect/flush behavior, preserving correctness while targeting a narrower IPC win than prior predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impac...","metadata":{"matches":36,"truncated":false},"title":"category.*structural|structural|IF/ID|pipeline|stage|bypass|forward|hazard|MEM/WB|EX/MEM","time":{"start":1778700902065,"end":1778700902088}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00f991d40473d50e016a04d265def4819a9e73d5d62947eec8"}},"id":"prt_e22d5deb0001KDhZDnXOcagyDR","sessionID":"ses_1dd2a561effeaTIjFEKGAY0mBG","messageID":"msg_e22d5aa22001ceR4zY3lROjJvg"}}
