{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778679209408,"sessionID":"ses_1de762601ffeqQ4Q0OHTLoh5cL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_1cahbImqfJZZUxFua6XorJbj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Bypass ready load data to EX\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current five-stage pipeline pays a mandatory one-cycle load-use bubble whenever the instruction immediately after a load consumes the loaded register. CoreMark's list and matrix kernels contain many pointer and array dependent loads, and the benchmark bus model often has dmem ready in the same cycle. Recovering those bubbles should improve iterations/cycle without changing the retirement width or adding the broad pipeline stalls that hurt the prior structural M-unit attempt.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a MEM-to-EX load-result bypass path for the specific case where the instruction in EX/MEM is a load, dmem is ready, and the younger ID/EX instruction uses that load's rd. The MEM stage already computes sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally before the MEM/WB register; expose that value and let the forwarding network select it for EX operands when dmem_ready is high. Keep the existing load-use interlock only for dmem stalls or cases where the load data is not yet ready, so correctness and RVFI ordering remain unchanged while ready loads avoid the one-cycle bubble.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"If needed, add a compact forwarding selector encoding for the new MEM-stage load-data bypass while preserving existing pipeline bundle semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the combinational sign/zero-extended load_data and a valid load-bypass indication before the MEM/WB register.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Prefer ready EX/MEM load-data forwarding over the old load-use stall path when the dependent EX operand matches the load destination.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Suppress the classic load-use bubble only when the load in EX/MEM can provide ready bypass data; retain stalls when dmem is not ready.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add an operand mux input for MEM-stage load bypass data and feed it through the existing ALU, branch, store-data, and RVFI rs data paths.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire dmem_ready-qualified MEM load bypass signals between mem_stage, forward_unit, hazard_unit, and ex_stage without changing the nret=1 top-level IO.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Bypass ready load data to EX\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current five-stage pipeline pays a mandatory one-cycle load-use bubble whenever the instruction immediately after a load consumes the loaded register. CoreMark's list and matrix kernels contain many pointer and array dependent loads, and the benchmark bus model often has dmem ready in the same cycle. Recovering those bubbles should improve iterations/cycle without changing the retirement width or adding the broad pipeline stalls that hurt the prior structural M-unit attempt.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a MEM-to-EX load-result bypass path for the specific case where the instruction in EX/MEM is a load, dmem is ready, and the younger ID/EX instruction uses that load's rd. The MEM stage already computes sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally before the MEM/WB register; expose that value and let the forwarding network select it for EX operands when dmem_ready is high. Keep the existing load-use interlock only for dmem stalls or cases where the load data is not yet ready, so correctness and RVFI ordering remain unchanged while ready loads avoid the one-cycle bubble.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"If needed, add a compact forwarding selector encoding for the new MEM-stage load-data bypass while preserving existing pipeline bundle semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the combinational sign/zero-extended load_data and a valid load-bypass indication before the MEM/WB register.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Prefer ready EX/MEM load-data forwarding over the old load-use stall path when the dependent EX operand matches the load destination.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Suppress the classic load-use bubble only when the load in EX/MEM can provide ready bypass data; retain stalls when dmem is not ready.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add an operand mux input for MEM-stage load bypass data and feed it through the existing ALU, branch, store-data, and RVFI rs data paths.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire dmem_ready-qualified MEM load bypass signals between mem_stage, forward_unit, hazard_unit, and ex_stage without changing the nret=1 top-level IO.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Bypass ready load data to EX\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current five-stage pipeline pays a mandatory one-cycle load-use bubble whenever the instruction immediately after a load consumes the loaded register. CoreMark's list and matrix kernels contain many pointer and array dependent loads, and the benchmark bus model often has dmem ready in the same cycle. Recovering those bubbles should improve iterations/cycle without changing the retirement width or adding the broad pipeline stalls that hurt the prior structural M-unit attempt.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a MEM-to-EX load-result bypass path for the specific case where the instruction in EX/MEM is a load, dmem is ready, and the younger ID/EX instruction uses that load's rd. The MEM stage already computes sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally before the MEM/WB register; expose that value and let the forwarding network select it for EX operands when dmem_ready is high. Keep the existing load-use interlock only for dmem stalls or cases where the load data is not yet ready, so correctness and RVFI ordering remain unchanged while ready loads avoid the one-cycle bubble.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"If needed, add a compact forwarding select