{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778689216005,"sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","part":{"id":"prt_e22238e04001uHAeBxstIYd2XM","messageID":"msg_e222389e50013HHsyAM9TYXQne","sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","snapshot":"3d6de4bb93dc406ae086c7d08dad111fe7d4e1d6","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778689237129,"sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","part":{"id":"prt_e2223d999001DxP6400QW6D21N","messageID":"msg_e222389e50013HHsyAM9TYXQne","sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","type":"text","text":"The prior structural attempts show broad latency/control changes regressed, while the only structural win was pure retiming of PC arithmetic into ID. I’m going to propose another narrow retiming hypothesis rather than a new predictor, buffer, or multicycle unit.","time":{"start":1778689235353,"end":1778689237127},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0fae551522dfc854016a04a4d33e9c819b98922f864e7b946f","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778689257841,"sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","part":{"id":"prt_e22242aec0018sFVa6HaxHxr4E","messageID":"msg_e222389e50013HHsyAM9TYXQne","sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","type":"text","text":"I’ll write a single structural hypothesis for a one-entry fetch skid buffer that is only meant to decouple front-end fetch from backend data-memory holds, avoiding the failed always-registered IF/ID approach.","time":{"start":1778689256172,"end":1778689257840},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0fae551522dfc854016a04a4e80efc819bb1e7003f91870c20","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778689277953,"sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_0VjmYL81y5NBseSQXVQy6jvj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The benchmark model injects independent instruction and data bus stalls, and the current pipeline freezes fetch whenever a data-memory operation is held in EX/MEM. If instruction memory is ready during that backend hold, the core wastes an opportunity to capture the next sequential instruction and can then immediately lose more cycles to a later imem stall after dmem unblocks.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that always inserted an IF/ID register or added store-buffer control regressed, so this hypothesis keeps the normal zero-wait path combinational and only adds a one-entry skid slot for cycles where the backend is already unable to advance.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry fetch skid buffer in the IF stage that captures the current imem instruction and PC when dmem_stall holds ID/EX and EX/MEM but imemReady is high. When the backend releases, feed the buffered instruction to ID before requesting/advancing to the next PC; invalidate the buffer on any EX redirect so wrong-path contents never retire.\n+\n+  This should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle under the random stall model by overlapping useful instruction fetch with data-memory wait cycles, without changing retirement width, branch resolution point, load-use behavior, or the hot EX arithmetic datapath. Because the buffer is bypassed in ordinary no-stall cycles, it should avoid the Fmax and branch-latency costs seen with a full registered IF/ID boundary.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Pass backend data-stall context into fetch separately from generic stall so IF can decide when to fill or drain a one-entry skid buffer.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry valid/pc/instruction skid buffer that captures ready imem responses during backend holds, bypasses during normal operation, drains before new fetch advance, and clears on reset or redirect.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the dmem-stall condition or equivalent backend-hold signal without weakening existing load-use, imem-stall, redirect, or MEM/WB hold priorities.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The benchmark model injects independent instruction and data bus stalls, and the current pipeline freezes fetch whenever a data-memory operation is held in EX/MEM. If instruction memory is ready during that backend hold, the core wastes an opportunity to capture the next sequential instruction and can then immediately lose more cycles to a later imem stall after dmem unblocks.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that always inserted an IF/ID register or added store-buffer control regressed, so this hypothesis keeps the normal zero-wait path combinational and only adds a one-entry skid slot for cycles where the backend is already unable to advance.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry fetch skid buffer in the IF stage that captures the current imem instruction and PC when dmem_stall holds ID/EX and EX/MEM but imemReady is high. When the backend releases, feed the buffered instruction to ID before requesting/advancing to the next PC; invalidate the buffer on any EX redirect so wrong-path contents never retire.\n+\n+  This should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle under the random stall model by overlapping useful instruction fetch with data-memory wait cycles, without changing retirement width, branch resolution point, load-use behavior, or the hot EX arithmetic datapath. Because the buffer is bypassed in ordinary no-stall cycles, it should avoid the Fmax and branch-latency costs seen with a full registered IF/ID boundary.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Pass backend data-stall context into fetch separately from generic stall so IF can decide when to fill or drain a one-entry skid buffer.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry valid/pc/instruction skid buffer that captures ready imem responses during backend holds, bypasses during normal operation, drains before new fetch advance, and clears on reset or redirect.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the dmem-stall condition or equivalent backend-hold signal without weakening existing load-use, imem-stall, redirect, or MEM/WB hold priorities.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The benchmark model injects independent instruction and data bus stalls, and the current pipeline freezes fetch whenever a data-memory operation is held in EX/MEM. If instruction memory is ready during that backend hold, the core wastes an opportunity to capture the next sequential instruction and can then immediately lose more cycles to a later imem stall after dmem unblocks.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that always inserted an IF/ID register or added store-buffer control regressed, so this hypothesis keeps the normal zero-wait path combinational and only adds a one-entry skid slot for cycles where the backend is already unable to advance.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry fetch skid buffer in the IF stage that captures the current imem instruction and PC when dmem_stall holds ID/EX and EX/MEM but imemReady is high. When the backend releases, feed the buffered instruction to ID before requesting/advancing to the next PC; invalidate the buffer on any EX redirect so wrong-path contents never retire.\n+\n+  This should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle under the random stall model by overlapping useful instruction fetch with data-memory wait cycles, without changing retirement width, branch resolution point, load-use behavior, or the hot EX arithmetic datapath. Because the buffer is bypassed in ordinary no-stall cycles, it should avoid the Fmax and branch-latency costs seen with a full registered IF/ID boundary.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Pass backend data-stall context into fetch separately from generic stall so IF can decide when to fill or drain a one-entry skid buffer.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry valid/pc/instruction skid buffer that captures ready imem responses during backend holds, bypasses during normal operation, drains before new fetch advance, and clears on reset or redirect.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the dmem-stall condition or equivalent backend-hold signal without weakening existing load-use, imem-stall, redirect, or MEM/WB hold priorities.\"\n","additions":21,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778689277948,"end":1778689277952}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0fae551522dfc854016a04a4e9bf04819b8bf8141f7c07150c"}},"id":"prt_e22243171002HR97Nka0rZjeP8","sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","messageID":"msg_e222389e50013HHsyAM9TYXQne"}}
