{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778689284411,"sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_v4qlH1Vd6doVyvytf6Acw3Fw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n2: title: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The benchmark model injects independent instruction and data bus stalls, and the current pipeline freezes fetch whenever a data-memory operation is held in EX/MEM. If instruction memory is ready during that backend hold, the core wastes an opportunity to capture the next sequential instruction and can then immediately lose more cycles to a later imem stall after dmem unblocks.\n6: \n7:   Prior structural attempts that always inserted an IF/ID register or added store-buffer control regressed, so this hypothesis keeps the normal zero-wait path combinational and only adds a one-entry skid slot for cycles where the backend is already unable to advance.\n8: hypothesis: |\n9:   Add a one-entry fetch skid buffer in the IF stage that captures the current imem instruction and PC when dmem_stall holds ID/EX and EX/MEM but imemReady is high. When the backend releases, feed the buffered instruction to ID before requesting/advancing to the next PC; invalidate the buffer on any EX redirect so wrong-path contents never retire.\n10: \n11:   This should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle under the random stall model by overlapping useful instruction fetch with data-memory wait cycles, without changing retirement width, branch resolution point, load-use behavior, or the hot EX arithmetic datapath. Because the buffer is bypassed in ordinary no-stall cycles, it should avoid the Fmax and branch-latency costs seen with a full registered IF/ID boundary.\n12: expected_impact:\n13:   fitness_delta_pct: 4\n14:   confidence: medium\n15: changes:\n16:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n17:     description: \"Pass backend data-stall context into fetch separately from generic stall so IF can decide when to fill or drain a one-entry skid buffer.\"\n18:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n19:     description: \"Add a one-entry valid/pc/instruction skid buffer that captures ready imem responses during backend holds, bypasses during normal operation, drains before new fetch advance, and clears on reset or redirect.\"\n20:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n21:     description: \"Expose the dmem-stall condition or equivalent backend-hold signal without weakening existing load-use, imem-stall, redirect, or MEM/WB hold priorities.\"\n\n(End of file - total 21 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\ntitle: \"Add fetch skid buffer\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The benchmark model injects independent instruction and data bus stalls, and the current pipeline freezes fetch whenever a data-memory operation is held in EX/MEM. If instruction memory is ready during that backend hold, the core wastes an opportunity to capture the next sequential instruction and can then immediately lose more cycles to a later imem stall after dmem unblocks.\n\n  Prior structural attempts that always inserted an IF/ID register or added store-buffer control regressed, so this hypothesis keeps the normal zero-wait path combinational and only adds a one-entry skid slot for cycles where the backend is already unable to advance.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a one-entry fetch skid buffer in the IF stage that captures the current imem instruction and PC when dmem_stall holds ID/EX and EX/MEM but imemReady is high. When the backend releases, feed the buffered instruction to ID before requesting/advancing to the next PC; invalidate the buffer on any EX redirect so wrong-path contents never retire.\n\n  This should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle under the random stall model by overlapping useful instruction fetch with data-memory wait cycles, without changing retirement width, branch resolution point, load-use behavior, or the hot EX arithmetic datapath. Because the buffer is bypassed in ordinary no-stall cycles, it should avoid the Fmax and branch-latency costs seen with a full registered IF/ID boundary.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Pass backend data-stall context into fetch separately from generic stall so IF can decide when to fill or drain a one-entry skid buffer.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add a one-entry valid/pc/instruction skid buffer that captures ready imem responses during backend holds, bypasses during normal operation, drains before new fetch advance, and clears on reset or redirect.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778689284394,"end":1778689284410}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0385fe40c6257882016a04a503c7d081999b927acdc85ffc88"}},"id":"prt_e22249764002tS6GA2nCshus31","sessionID":"ses_1dddcae5dffevV2cuCQEYur7PA","messageID":"msg_e2224807b001G9ezsG1iB1iJa5"}}
