{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778695079832,"sessionID":"ses_1dd83ee70ffey6McjJC1b4jHpl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_0jZdyG6xDSQcPvmQv21Mgqks","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Bypass ALU for memory addresses\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current EX stage routes load and store effective-address generation through\n+  the same combinational ALU result mux used for arithmetic, branches, jumps,\n+  and RV32M operations. CoreMark executes many memory operations, so their MEM\n+  address path can inherit unnecessary muxing and arithmetic fanout even though\n+  the required operation is only rs1 + immediate.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that added front-end state, store queues, or load\n+  bypasses regressed because they added control complexity or new critical\n+  paths. A narrower structural split inside EX keeps the pipeline timing and IPC\n+  identical while trying to shorten a hot address-generation path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a dedicated simple effective-address adder in rtl/ex_stage.sv for\n+  load/store instructions, fed by the existing forwarded rs1 value and the\n+  registered immediate. When mem_read or mem_write is set, capture this adder's\n+  result into ex_mem.alu_result instead of the general ALU output; all other\n+  instructions keep the existing ALU, branch, jump, AUIPC, and RVFI behavior.\n+\n+  This should let synthesis keep memory address generation out of the wider ALU\n+  result cone that also contains M-extension and comparison cases, potentially\n+  improving Fmax without changing retirement width, load-use interlocks, dmem\n+  stall behavior, or RVFI metadata. Because the change is a local retiming/split\n+  and not a predictor or buffer, it has lower correctness and formal risk than\n+  the failed structural experiments.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated rs1+imm effective-address adder for loads and stores and select it for ex_mem.alu_result when mem_read or mem_write is asserted.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,33 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Bypass ALU for memory addresses\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current EX stage routes load and store effective-address generation through\n+  the same combinational ALU result mux used for arithmetic, branches, jumps,\n+  and RV32M operations. CoreMark executes many memory operations, so their MEM\n+  address path can inherit unnecessary muxing and arithmetic fanout even though\n+  the required operation is only rs1 + immediate.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that added front-end state, store queues, or load\n+  bypasses regressed because they added control complexity or new critical\n+  paths. A narrower structural split inside EX keeps the pipeline timing and IPC\n+  identical while trying to shorten a hot address-generation path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a dedicated simple effective-address adder in rtl/ex_stage.sv for\n+  load/store instructions, fed by the existing forwarded rs1 value and the\n+  registered immediate. When mem_read or mem_write is set, capture this adder's\n+  result into ex_mem.alu_result instead of the general ALU output; all other\n+  instructions keep the existing ALU, branch, jump, AUIPC, and RVFI behavior.\n+\n+  This should let synthesis keep memory address generation out of the wider ALU\n+  result cone that also contains M-extension and comparison cases, potentially\n+  improving Fmax without changing retirement width, load-use interlocks, dmem\n+  stall behavior, or RVFI metadata. Because the change is a local retiming/split\n+  and not a predictor or buffer, it has lower correctness and formal risk than\n+  the failed structural experiments.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a dedicated rs1+imm effective-address adder for loads and stores and select it for ex_mem.alu_result when mem_read or mem_write is asserted.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,33 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Bypass ALU for memory addresses\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current EX stage routes load and store effective-address generation through\n+  the same combinational ALU 