{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778696166815,"sessionID":"ses_1dd739f70ffedZzR8LMWpG36gh","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ab2K41aG638D6idocTbiHwnZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r8s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r8s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\n2: title: \"Qualify load-use interlock sources\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 fields of the following instruction, even when the following opcode does not actually read one of those fields. That can inject unnecessary bubbles after loads in CoreMark's pointer-heavy code, reducing iterations/cycle without improving correctness.\n6: \n7:   A prior attempt at source qualification broke because it used opcode-level approximations and changed ID/EX operand metadata. The safer structural version is to add exact decoder-produced source-use bits and use them only in the hazard decision, leaving RVFI rs addresses/data and the existing forwarding metadata unchanged.\n8: hypothesis: |\n9:   Extend the decoder/control path with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 bits that are cleared only for instruction forms that architecturally do not read the corresponding register field. Feed those bits for the current IF/ID instruction into hazard_unit, and gate the load-use comparisons so a load only stalls when the younger instruction truly consumes the loaded rd.\n10: \n11:   This should recover occasional false load-use bubbles for OP-IMM, LOAD, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK-like instructions while preserving the existing five-stage topology, RVFI metadata, single-retire nret=1 contract, and conservative real load-use stalls. The change adds no data bypass path, no predictor state, and no dmem/imem queueing, so the main risk is modest front-end control timing from the extra source-use decode.\n12: expected_impact:\n13:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n14:   confidence: medium\n15: changes:\n16:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n17:     description: \"Add source-use bits to ctrl_t so decode can carry exact architectural rs1/rs2 consumption without altering RVFI operand metadata.\"\n18:   - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n19:     description: \"Drive uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 exactly for each legal RV32IM instruction class, keeping illegal defaults conservative and preserving decoder illegal-instruction invariants.\"\n20:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n21:     description: \"Latch the decoder source-use bits into ID/EX control and expose the current IF/ID decode result for hazard qualification without zeroing rs fields.\"\n22:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n23:     description: \"Gate load-use rs comparisons with exact uses_rs1/uses_rs2 so only true consumers of a pending load insert the one-cycle bubble.\"\n24:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n25:     description: \"Wire the source-use hazard inputs from decode to hazard_unit while preserving the existing nret=1 top-level port set and retirement path.\"\n\n(End of file - total 25 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\ntitle: \"Qualify load-use interlock sources\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 fields of the following instruction, even when the following opcode does not actually read one of those fields. That can inject unnecessary bubbles after loads in CoreMark's pointer-heavy code, reducing iterations/cycle without improving correctness.\n\n  A prior attempt at source qualification broke because it used opcode-level approximations and changed ID/EX operand metadata. The safer structural version is to add exact decoder-produced source-use bits and use them only in the hazard decision, leaving RVFI rs addresses/data and the existing forwarding metadata unchanged.\nhypothesis: |\n  Extend the decoder/control path with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 bits that are cleared only for instruction forms that architecturally do not read the corresponding register field. Feed those bits for the current IF/ID instruction into hazard_unit, and gate the load-use comparisons so a load only stalls when the younger instruction truly consumes the loaded rd.\n\n  This should recover occasional false load-use bubbles for OP-IMM, LOAD, LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK-like instructions while preserving the existing five-stage topology, RVFI metadata, single-retire nret=1 contract, and conservative real load-use stalls. The change adds no data bypass path, no predictor state, and no dmem/imem queueing, so the main risk is modest front-end control timing from the extra source-use decode.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add source-use bits to ctrl_t so decode can carry exact architectural rs1/rs2 consumption without altering RVFI operand metadata.\"\n  - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n    description: \"Drive uses_rs1 and uses_rs2 exactly for each legal RV32IM instruction class, keeping illegal defaults conservative and preserving decoder illegal-instruction invariants.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r8s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778696166812,"end":1778696166815}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b614deb4f2fff0b016a04bfe58d98819a83a64dddda8da3b2"}},"id":"prt_e228d99db001GC9DhgKGrTU7H5","sessionID":"ses_1dd739f70ffedZzR8LMWpG36gh","messageID":"msg_e228d857c001kp4I5BzLa25JMR"}}
