{"type":"text","timestamp":1778700919820,"sessionID":"ses_1dd2a56f3ffeW1CZMypEbK3ASR","part":{"id":"prt_e22d61a510027xfXziofxaZ3Jw","messageID":"msg_e22d5dd84001ScETG6AZTuEM5d","sessionID":"ses_1dd2a56f3ffeW1CZMypEbK3ASR","type":"text","text":"The predictor history is consistently negative for anything that adds fetch-PC speculation, decode-to-PC target generation, or wide predicted-PC metadata. I’m writing a deliberately narrow predictor hypothesis that keeps normal fetch untouched and uses EX-trained loop information only to bias a redirect-cycle target injection path, with low confidence and explicit rollback conditions.","time":{"start":1778700917330,"end":1778700919819},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_08ffa14c2114f964016a04d27534ec819ba4f8bb4e083d9923","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778700939952,"sessionID":"ses_1dd2a56f3ffeW1CZMypEbK3ASR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_HhLLz3IoVxuQAwz6kOc4dwlp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r13s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r13s2\n+title: \"Predict redirect target valid\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior predictor attempts for this core show that normal fetch cannot afford extra decode-to-PC logic, BTB arrays, RAS state, or wide predicted-PC validation metadata. CoreMark still has repeated taken loop backedges, but the least risky remaining predictor angle is to keep the architectural fetch PC policy unchanged and only learn whether a redirect target instruction can be safely reused during the already-existing redirect bubble.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry EX-trained loop redirect predictor that stores a taken backward branch PC, its target PC, and a confidence bit indicating that the first target instruction was observed cleanly on a prior redirect. On a later matching taken branch, do not suppress the EX redirect and do not predict the fetch PC early; instead, let EX redirect exactly as today while allowing IF to present the cached target instruction as the redirect-cycle IF/ID payload only when the target PC matches, imem is ready, and no data-memory hold is active.\n+\n+  This is narrower than the failed target-instruction cache attempt: it should avoid branch-PC compares on the normal next-PC mux, avoid predicted_pc_next metadata in RVFI, and make the cache valid only after observing a clean target fetch. The expected upside is small, but it may recover one bubble on hot loop backedges while keeping the proven five-stage control path and all misprediction recovery in EX.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 1\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add minimal IF/ID metadata needed to mark a redirect-injected target instruction as valid without adding predicted_pc_next fields to retirement metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry redirect target instruction predictor/cache trained only after a clean redirected target fetch and used only during matching EX redirect cycles.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose resolved taken-backward-branch training signals and keep normal EX redirect/RVFI pc_next behavior authoritative.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the EX training signals and IF redirect-injection controls while preserving the nret=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r13s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r13s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r13s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r13s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r13s2\n+title: \"Predict redirect target valid\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior predictor attempts for this core show that normal fetch cannot afford extra decode-to-PC logic, BTB arrays, RAS state, or wide predicted-PC validation metadata. CoreMark still has repeated taken loop backedges, but the least risky remaining predictor angle is to keep the architectural fetch PC policy unchanged and only learn whether a redirect target instruction can be safely reused during the already-existing redirect bubble.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry EX-trained loop redirect predictor that stores a 