{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778702006712,"sessionID":"ses_1dd1aec5affefVRWlACOmwbImZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_g7fhCPPUed4brpyMDoamy5W7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-003-r14s2\n2: title: \"Delayed loop predictor\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current core still loses two younger instructions on every taken loop\n6:   branch, but prior predictor attempts show that same-cycle fetch PC tag\n7:   compares, decode-immediate redirects, BTB/RAS state, and redirect-cycle\n8:   instruction injection usually cost more FPGA timing than they recover.\n9:   A predictor experiment is still worthwhile only if it avoids adding logic to\n10:   the normal imem_data-to-PC or PC-tag-hit-to-PC critical path.\n11: hypothesis: |\n12:   Add a one-entry delayed loop predictor trained only by resolved taken\n13:   backward conditional branches. During fetch, compare the current registered\n14:   PC against the learned branch PC and register the hit/target metadata, but\n15:   do not use that same-cycle compare to choose the next PC. One cycle later,\n16:   while the branch is in decode, use the registered hit to redirect fetch to\n17:   the stored target and carry the exact predicted target with that branch into\n18:   EX. EX suppresses the normal taken-branch redirect only when the carried\n19:   prediction matches the resolved target; otherwise it falls back to the\n20:   existing redirect and flush behavior.\n21: \n22:   This deliberately recovers at most one of the two taken-branch penalty\n23:   cycles, but it removes the predictor tag compare from the fetch PC update\n24:   cone that hurt previous one-entry loop predictors. It also avoids decode\n25:   immediate generation for prediction, arrays, counters, JAL/JALR/RAS cases,\n26:   and redirect-target instruction caching. The expected upside is modest, but\n27:   this is the narrowest remaining predictor-only path that can improve loop\n28:   IPC without recreating the known Tang Nano timing regressions.\n29: expected_impact:\n30:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n31:   confidence: low\n32: changes:\n33:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n34:     description: \"Add compact carried prediction fields to IF/ID and ID/EX for delayed loop hits: predicted valid and predicted target for the exact fetched branch.\"\n35:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n36:     description: \"Add a single-entry EX-trained backward-branch predictor whose PC compare result is registered for next-cycle use, then redirect fetch from that registered hit rather than the same-cycle compare.\"\n37:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n38:     description: \"Train the delayed predictor from resolved taken backward branches and suppress the normal branch redirect only when the carried predicted target exactly matches the resolved target.\"\n39:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n40:     description: \"Wire delayed predictor update and carried prediction metadata between IF, ID, and EX without changing the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n\n(End of file - total 40 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-003-r14s2\ntitle: \"Delayed loop predictor\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current core still loses two younger instructions on every taken loop\n  branch, but prior predictor attempts show that same-cycle fetch PC tag\n  compares, decode-immediate redirects, BTB/RAS state, and redirect-cycle\n  instruction injection usually cost more FPGA timing than they recover.\n  A predictor experiment is still worthwhile only if it avoids adding logic to\n  the normal imem_data-to-PC or PC-tag-hit-to-PC critical path.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a one-entry delayed loop predictor trained only by resolved taken\n  backward conditional branches. During fetch, compare the current registered\n  PC against the learned branch PC and register the hit/target metadata, but\n  do not use that same-cycle compare to choose the next PC. One cycle later,\n  while the branch is in decode, use the registered hit to redirect fetch to\n  the stored target and carry the exact predicted target with that branch into\n  EX. EX suppresses the normal taken-branch redirect only when the carried\n  prediction matches the resolved target; otherwise it falls back to the\n  existing redirect and flush behavior.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778702006705,"end":1778702006711}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03194a31e1146ef4016a04d6b5ec3c8199b107550f6775c538"}},"id":"prt_e22e6b7130019ustToat9Sjkmx","sessionID":"ses_1dd1aec5affefVRWlACOmwbImZ","messageID":"msg_e22e6a107001HT37pvqJyXlH0y"}}
