{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778703120182,"sessionID":"ses_1dd0982e5ffewX9K3S6ymzWTPv","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_nB0EQMKDJsnyVetu1QC9aXR6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r15s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r15s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-003-r15s2\n2: title: \"Use stalls for loop prediction\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   Prior predictor attempts on this core consistently lost fitness when they added tag compares, target muxes, decode immediates, or predicted-PC metadata to the normal zero-wait fetch path. CoreMark still spends cycles on taken loop backedges, but the random imem stall model creates cycles where fetch is already unable to deliver the sequential instruction. A predictor that only acts during those otherwise-lost stall windows may recover some loop-target latency without slowing the common fetch path.\n6: hypothesis: |\n7:   Add a one-entry EX-trained loop predictor for resolved taken backward conditional branches, but do not let it affect the normal `next_pc = pc + 4` fetch update when `io_imemReady` is high. When the current fetch PC matches the learned branch PC while `io_imemReady` is low, pre-arm a registered predicted target for the next cycle; if the pipeline is still waiting on instruction memory or is just resuming from the stall, use that registered target to redirect fetch and mark the branch with carried predicted metadata so EX can suppress only the matching taken redirect.\n8: \n9:   This intentionally recovers less than a full same-cycle predictor, but it keeps the PC tag compare and target selection off the common zero-wait fetch path that hurt previous predictors. The expected win is from hiding part of hot loop backedge recovery under random instruction stalls, with low LUT/state cost and no BTB arrays, RAS logic, decode-time immediates, or jump prediction.\n10: expected_impact:\n11:   fitness_delta_pct: 1\n12:   confidence: low\n13: changes:\n14:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n15:     description: \"Add compact carried prediction fields for a stall-armed loop prediction: predicted valid, predicted branch PC, and predicted target.\"\n16:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n17:     description: \"Train a single registered loop predictor from EX, arm it only on PC-tag hits during imem stalls, and apply the registered target only outside the normal zero-wait fetch path.\"\n18:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n19:     description: \"Export resolved taken-backward branch training information and suppress the normal redirect only when the carried stall-armed prediction exactly matches the resolving branch and target.\"\n20:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n21:     description: \"Wire loop-predictor training, carried prediction metadata, and redirect suppression between IF and EX without changing the nret=1 RVFI interface.\"\n\n(End of file - total 21 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-003-r15s2\ntitle: \"Use stalls for loop prediction\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Prior predictor attempts on this core consistently lost fitness when they added tag compares, target muxes, decode immediates, or predicted-PC metadata to the normal zero-wait fetch path. CoreMark still spends cycles on taken loop backedges, but the random imem stall model creates cycles where fetch is already unable to deliver the sequential instruction. A predictor that only acts during those otherwise-lost stall windows may recover some loop-target latency without slowing the common fetch path.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a one-entry EX-trained loop predictor for resolved taken backward conditional branches, but do not let it affect the normal `next_pc = pc + 4` fetch update when `io_imemReady` is high. When the current fetch PC matches the learned branch PC while `io_imemReady` is low, pre-arm a registered predicted target for the next cycle; if the pipeline is still waiting on instruction memory or is just resuming from the stall, use that registered target to redirect fetch and mark the branch with carried predicted metadata so EX can suppress only the matching taken redirect.\n\n  This intentionally recovers less than a full same-cycle predictor, but it keeps the PC tag compare and target selection off the common zero-wait fetch path that hurt previous predictors. The expected win is from hiding part of hot loop backedge recovery under random instruction stalls, with low LUT/state cost and no BTB arrays, RAS logic, decode-time immediates, or jump prediction.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 1\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add compact carried prediction fields for a stall-armed loop prediction: predicted valid, predicted branch PC, and predicted target.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Train a single registered loop predictor from EX, arm it only on PC-tag hits during imem stalls, and apply the registered target only outside the normal zero-wait fetch path.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Export resolved taken-backward branch training information and suppress the normal redirect only when the carried stall-armed prediction exactly matches the resolving branch and target.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r15s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778703120174,"end":1778703120181}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b7251c65a53374d016a04db0f9e9c819ba54f19525bcbf8d9"}},"id":"prt_e22f7b582001NERv11xqxLCS5R","sessionID":"ses_1dd0982e5ffewX9K3S6ymzWTPv","messageID":"msg_e22f799c4001joIDC1TCUdZ8i1"}}
