rd. The MEM stage already computes sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally before the MEM/WB register; expose that value and let the forwarding network select it for EX operands when dmem_ready is high. Keep the existing load-use interlock only for dmem stalls or cases where the load data is not yet ready, so correctness and RVFI ordering remain unchanged while ready loads avoid the one-cycle bubble.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"If needed, add a compact forwarding selector encoding for the new MEM-stage load-data bypass while preserving existing pipeline bundle semantics.\"}, {\"file\"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Correct ID backward-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core pays a two-instruction flush penalty on every taken conditional branch because branches resolve in EX and fetch is effectively static not-taken. CoreMark's inner loops should contain frequent backward taken branches, so recovering even part of that penalty can improve iterations per cycle without touching the already successful M-extension ALU optimization.\\n\\nThe previous predictor attempt identified the right low-cost direction but failed because EX compared against IF fall-through metadata rather than the branch's decoded target, so nominally correct backward predictions still looked wrong. A corrected metadata path is the most promising predictor-only follow-up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core pays a two-instruction flush penalty on every taken conditional branch because branches resolve in EX and fetch is effectively static not-taken. CoreMark's inner loops should contain frequent backward taken branches, so recovering even part of that penalty can improve iterations per cycle without touching the already successful M-extension ALU optimization.\\n\\nThe previous predictor attempt identified the right low-cost direction but failed because EX compared against IF fall-through metadata rather than the branch's decoded target, so nominally correct backward predictions still looked wrong. A corrected metadata path is the most promising predictor-only follow-up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a minimal static predictor that operates after decode: when ID sees a valid conditional branch with a negative B-immediate, redirect fetch to the decoded branch target and mark that branch with predicted_taken and predicted_pc_next in the ID/EX payload. EX then computes the resolved next PC for branches and jumps and redirects only when resolved_pc_next differs from the carried predicted_pc_next.\\n\\nThis keeps th... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778680241822,"end":1778680241825}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05007d237a3c576f016a0481b182b0819b8c9c8de37d8fca65"}},"id":"prt_e219a9e0a001H5EHCeCBME6oJi","sessionID":"ses_1de65a0efffethTDFbccQ3rAe5","messageID":"msg_e219a8943001gmyag5ypiIgnv0"}}
