{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778684224184,"sessionID":"ses_1de299b11ffeD547owEKVaQwUa","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_r6miOpeFA5zPC7VBZONmG8PO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Predict JAL in decode\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current core resolves every taken control transfer in EX, so unconditional\n+  JAL instructions pay the same two-younger-instruction flush penalty as taken\n+  conditional branches. Prior predictor attempts showed that conditional\n+  backward prediction lengthened the imem/decode/target path and that mutable\n+  BTB arrays complicated formal convergence, so the next predictor experiment\n+  should target a smaller, deterministic subset of control flow.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a static early predictor only for valid JAL instructions in the decode\n+  stage. JAL is always taken and its target is encoded in the instruction, so ID\n+  can compute pc+J-immediate and redirect fetch one cycle earlier without any\n+  dynamic predictor state, branch comparison, or BTB tag lookup. Carry a\n+  predicted_pc_next bit/value through ID/EX and EX/MEM so EX suppresses the\n+  normal redirect when the resolved JAL target matches the decode prediction,\n+  while branches and JALR keep the existing EX-resolution behavior.\n+\n+  This should recover some CoreMark IPC on function-call and unconditional-jump\n+  paths while avoiding the two known predictor hazards: conditional decode\n+  prediction on every branch and mutable fetch-side predictor arrays. The change\n+  is intentionally narrow and should be easier for riscv-formal than a BTB.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted next-PC metadata to the IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM pipeline bundles for early JAL prediction accounting.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire a decode-stage JAL prediction redirect into fetch and pass prediction metadata through the pipeline without changing the NRET=1 RVFI port shape.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Detect legal JAL opcodes, compute their J-immediate target, request an early fetch redirect, and annotate the decoded instruction with predicted_pc_next.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Accept an early decode redirect for predicted JAL targets with lower priority than EX mispredict recovery and reset handling.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compare resolved next PC with carried predicted_pc_next and only assert redirect when the prediction was absent or incorrect.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,37 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Predict JAL in decode\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current core resolves every taken control transfer in EX, so unconditional\n+  JAL instructions pay the same two-younger-instruction flush penalty as taken\n+  conditional branches. Prior predictor attempts showed that conditional\n+  backward prediction lengthened the imem/decode/target path and that mutable\n+  BTB arrays complicated formal convergence, so the next predictor experiment\n+  should target a smaller, deterministic subset of control flow.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a static early predictor only for valid JAL instructions in the decode\n+  stage. JAL is always taken and its target is encoded in the instruction, so ID\n+  can compute pc+J-immediate and redirect fetch one cycle earlier without any\n+  dynamic predictor state, branch comparison, or BTB tag lookup. Carry a\n+  predicted_pc_next bit/value through ID/EX and EX/MEM so EX suppresses the\n+  normal redirect when the resolved JAL target matches the decode prediction,\n+  while branches and JALR keep the existing EX-resolution behavior.\n+\n+  This should recover some CoreMark IPC on function-call and unconditional-jump\n+  paths while avoiding the two known predictor hazards: conditional decode\n+  prediction on every branch and mutable fetch-side predictor arrays. The change\n+  is intentionally narrow and should be easier for riscv-formal than a BTB.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted next-PC metadata to the IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM pipeline bundles for early JAL prediction accounting.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire a decode-stage JAL prediction redirect into fetch and pass prediction metadata through the pipeline without changing the NRET=1 RVFI port shape.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Detect legal JAL opcodes, compute their J-immediate target, request an early fetch redirect, and annotate the decoded instruction with predicted_pc_next.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Accept an early decode redirect for predicted JAL targets with lower priority than EX mispredict recovery and reset handling.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compare resolved next PC with carried predicted_pc_next and only assert redirect when the prediction was absent or incorrect.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/g