{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778684231907,"sessionID":"ses_1de299b11ffeD547owEKVaQwUa","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_U1jILAjL3SaJbhndKr1qKN3s","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\n2: title: \"Predict JAL in decode\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current core resolves every taken control transfer in EX, so unconditional\n6:   JAL instructions pay the same two-younger-instruction flush penalty as taken\n7:   conditional branches. Prior predictor attempts showed that conditional\n8:   backward prediction lengthened the imem/decode/target path and that mutable\n9:   BTB arrays complicated formal convergence, so the next predictor experiment\n10:   should target a smaller, deterministic subset of control flow.\n11: hypothesis: |\n12:   Add a static early predictor only for valid JAL instructions in the decode\n13:   stage. JAL is always taken and its target is encoded in the instruction, so ID\n14:   can compute pc+J-immediate and redirect fetch one cycle earlier without any\n15:   dynamic predictor state, branch comparison, or BTB tag lookup. Carry a\n16:   predicted_pc_next bit/value through ID/EX and EX/MEM so EX suppresses the\n17:   normal redirect when the resolved JAL target matches the decode prediction,\n18:   while branches and JALR keep the existing EX-resolution behavior.\n19: \n20:   This should recover some CoreMark IPC on function-call and unconditional-jump\n21:   paths while avoiding the two known predictor hazards: conditional decode\n22:   prediction on every branch and mutable fetch-side predictor arrays. The change\n23:   is intentionally narrow and should be easier for riscv-formal than a BTB.\n24: expected_impact:\n25:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n26:   confidence: low\n27: changes:\n28:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n29:     description: \"Add predicted next-PC metadata to the IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM pipeline bundles for early JAL prediction accounting.\"\n30:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n31:     description: \"Wire a decode-stage JAL prediction redirect into fetch and pass prediction metadata through the pipeline without changing the NRET=1 RVFI port shape.\"\n32:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n33:     description: \"Detect legal JAL opcodes, compute their J-immediate target, request an early fetch redirect, and annotate the decoded instruction with predicted_pc_next.\"\n34:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n35:     description: \"Accept an early decode redirect for predicted JAL targets with lower priority than EX mispredict recovery and reset handling.\"\n36:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n37:     description: \"Compare resolved next PC with carried predicted_pc_next and only assert redirect when the prediction was absent or incorrect.\"\n\n(End of file - total 37 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\ntitle: \"Predict JAL in decode\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current core resolves every taken control transfer in EX, so unconditional\n  JAL instructions pay the same two-younger-instruction flush penalty as taken\n  conditional branches. Prior predictor attempts showed that conditional\n  backward prediction lengthened the imem/decode/target path and that mutable\n  BTB arrays complicated formal convergence, so the next predictor experiment\n  should target a smaller, deterministic subset of control flow.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a static early predictor only for valid JAL instructions in the decode\n  stage. JAL is always taken and its target is encoded in the instruction, so ID\n  can compute pc+J-immediate and redirect fetch one cycle earlier without any\n  dynamic predictor state, branch comparison, or BTB tag lookup. Carry a\n  predicted_pc_next bit/value through ID/EX and EX/MEM so EX suppresses the\n  normal redirect when the resolved JAL target matches the decode prediction,\n  while branches and JALR keep the existing EX-resolution behavior.\n\n  This should recover some CoreMark IPC on function-call and unconditional-jump","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778684231894,"end":1778684231906}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0a6225b26faff465016a049146bc1c819a92eae1d96cf0bdd9"}},"id":"prt_e21d77cdd001R2kzXNLtvK7jV6","sessionID":"ses_1de299b11ffeD547owEKVaQwUa","messageID":"msg_e21d76340001AeqX6wEsmXoT1y"}}
