{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778695084530,"sessionID":"ses_1dd83eecfffeVt6cbYivQFYBs6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_aTkn2rDoWN4KTyVgaPsBNdcm","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\n+title: \"Cache repeated JAL targets\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The core still pays a two-younger-instruction flush for every taken control\n+  transfer. Prior predictor attempts show that decode-time target generation,\n+  conditional branch prediction, and general mutable BTBs tend to lose FPGA\n+  timing or formal convergence. A narrower predictor should target only a\n+  deterministic, always-taken control-flow class while keeping instruction\n+  decode and branch comparison out of the fetch PC critical path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry fetch-side target cache for repeated JAL PCs. The entry is\n+  updated in EX when a legal JAL resolves, storing valid, the JAL PC tag, and\n+  its already-computed pc_imm_target. Fetch compares only the registered PC\n+  against this one tag; on a hit it uses the stored target as the next PC and\n+  carries predicted_pc_next metadata with that instruction so EX can suppress\n+  the normal JAL redirect only when the resolved next PC exactly matches.\n+\n+  This differs from the failed JAL decode predictor by avoiding any\n+  imem_data-to-immediate-to-PC combinational path, and differs from the failed\n+  BTB by avoiding arrays, counters, conditional branches, and JALR targets.\n+  It should recover repeated unconditional jump penalties in CoreMark with a\n+  small amount of registered state and a single PC compare/mux.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted_pc_next and predicted_valid metadata to the IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM payloads so RVFI pc_wdata and redirect suppression stay aligned with the retiring instruction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry registered JAL target cache lookup on the fetch PC and drive next_pc from the cached target only on a tag hit, while preserving reset, stall, and redirect priority.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Update the JAL target cache from resolved legal JALs and suppress the normal JAL redirect only when the carried prediction exactly equals the resolved next PC; branches and JALR keep existing EX-resolution behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the JAL predictor update and prediction metadata between IF and EX without changing the nret=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\n+title: \"Cache repeated JAL targets\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The core still pays a two-younger-instruction flush for every taken control\n+  transfer. Prior predictor attempts show that decode-time target generation,\n+  conditional branch prediction, and general mutable BTBs tend to lose FPGA\n+  timing or formal convergence. A narrower predictor should target only a\n+  deterministic, always-taken control-flow class while keeping instruction\n+  decode and branch comparison out of the fetch PC critical path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry fetch-side target cache for repeated JAL PCs. The entry is\n+  updated in EX when a legal JAL resolves, storing valid, the JAL PC tag, and\n+  its already-computed pc_imm_target. Fetch compares only the registered PC\n+  against this one tag; on a hit it uses the stored target as the next PC and\n+  carries predicted_pc_next metadata with that instruction so EX can suppress\n+  the normal JAL redirect only when the resolved next PC exactly matches.\n+\n+  This differs from the failed JAL decode predictor by avoiding any\n+  imem_data-to-immediate-to-PC combinational path, and differs from the failed\n+  BTB by avoiding arrays, counters, conditional branches, and JALR targets.\n+  It should recover repeated unconditional jump penalties in CoreMark with a\n+  small amount of registered state and a single PC compare/mux.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted_pc_next and predicted_valid metadata to the IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM payloads so RVFI pc_wdata and redirect suppression stay aligned with the retiring instruction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry registered JAL target cache lookup on the fetch PC and drive next_pc from the cached target only on a tag hit, while preserving reset, stall, and redirect priority.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Update the JAL target cache from resolved legal JALs and suppress the normal JAL redirect only when the carried prediction exactly equals the resolved next PC; branches and JALR keep existing EX-resolution behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the JAL predictor update and prediction metadata between IF and EX without changing the nret=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-