{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778697355694,"sessionID":"ses_1dd613a29ffeM6oKbr6WpcI3ZE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_evPorN3DE8nHdBBHaMTNttbp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r9s2\n+title: \"One-bit loop prediction\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current core still pays the full EX redirect flush on every taken conditional branch, but prior predictor attempts show that decode redirects, BTB arrays, JAL/JALR target caches, and 32-bit predicted-PC metadata all cost more FPGA fitness than they recover. CoreMark still has hot loop backedges, so the remaining predictor opportunity is to make the predictor narrower rather than more capable.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry taken-branch target predictor for resolved backward conditional branches only. Fetch compares the registered PC against one learned branch PC tag and, on a hit, uses the stored target as the next PC while carrying only a one-bit predicted_taken flag with that instruction. EX suppresses the normal taken-branch redirect when the branch was predicted taken and actually resolves taken; on a predicted-taken branch that resolves not-taken, EX redirects to the already-registered fall-through pc_plus4 and clears or weakens the entry.\n+\n+  This intentionally avoids the failed ingredients from earlier predictor attempts: no decode-time immediate-to-PC path, no predictor array, no JAL/JALR/return prediction, and no 32-bit predicted_pc_next comparison through the pipeline. The cost is one PC tag compare, one target mux, one learned target register, and a single metadata bit, which may recover repeated loop-backedge flushes with less Fmax damage than previous predictor designs.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a single predicted_taken bit to the IF/ID, ID/EX, and EX/MEM metadata needed to validate a one-entry taken-branch prediction without carrying a full predicted PC value.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add one registered branch-PC tag and target learned from EX, predict only on an exact PC hit, and choose the stored target as next PC while marking the fetched instruction predicted_taken.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"For conditional branches, suppress the existing taken redirect when predicted_taken matches an actually taken branch; redirect to pc_plus4 on predicted-taken/not-taken misses and update or clear the one-entry predictor from resolved backward branches.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the resolved branch update signals from EX to IF and preserve the nret=1 RVFI interface and existing hazard/flush ordering.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r9s2\n+title: \"One-bit loop prediction\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current core still pays the full EX redirect flush on every taken conditional branch, but prior predictor attempts show that decode redirects, BTB arrays, JAL/JALR target caches, and 32-bit predicted-PC metadata all cost more FPGA fitness than they recover. CoreMark still has hot loop backedges, so the remaining predictor opportunit