e signals from EX to IF and preserve the nret=1 RVFI interface and existing hazard/flush ordering.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r9s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r9s2\n+title: \"One-bit loop prediction\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current core still pays the full EX redirect flush on every taken conditional branch, but prior predictor attempts show that decode redirects, BTB arrays, JAL/JALR target caches, and 32-bit predicted-PC metadata all cost more FPGA fitness than they recover. CoreMark still has hot loop backedges, so the remaining predictor opportunity is to make the predictor narrower rather than more capable.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry taken-branch target predictor for resolved backward conditional branches only. Fetch compares the registered PC against one learned branch PC tag and, on a hit, uses the stored target as the next PC while carrying only a one-bit predicted_taken flag with that instruction. EX suppresses the normal taken-branch redirect when the branch was predicted taken and actually resolves taken; on a predicted-taken branch that resolves not-taken, EX redirects to the already-registered fall-through pc_plus4 and clears or weakens the entry.\n+\n+  T